# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2024-bolivarian-youth-games
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The **2019 Bolivian protests**, also known as the **Pitita Revolution** (Spanish: *la Revolución de las Pititas*), were protests and marches from 21 October 2019 until late November of that year in Bolivia, in response to claims of electoral fraud in the 2019 general election of 20 October.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] After 11 November 2019, there were protests by supporters of the outgoing government in response to Jeanine Áñez becoming the acting president of Bolivia.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The claims of fraud were made after the suspension of the preliminary vote count, in which incumbent Evo Morales was not leading by a large enough margin (10%) to avoid a runoff, and the subsequent publication of the official count, in which Morales won by just over 10%.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Some international observers expressed concern over the integrity of the elections.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] While the majority of the demonstrations were peaceful, there were also numerous acts of violence.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Initial violence allegedly targeted opposition protesters.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Pro-MAS supporters were bused into opposition areas, given weapons, and were told to clear blockades, resulting in death and injury of opposition protesters.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] In the later weeks of the protests, senior members of the Movement for Socialism (MAS) and their families were victims of attacks, including vandalism and arson of their houses.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Morales denied the allegations and invited international observers to audit the electoral processes, promising to hold a runoff if any fraud was found, although initially refusing to be bound by the results of an audit.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Opposition leaders rejected the OAS audit, saying they hadn't been party to the agreement.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Subsequently, an audit team from the Organization of American States (OAS), with access provided by Bolivian authorities, worked to verify the integrity and reliability of the results.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Their preliminary report, released on 10 November 2019 questioned the integrity of the election results and recommended another "electoral process".
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Following the release of the OAS initial report, Morales announced the government would hold another full election (rather than a runoff).
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Morales, together with his Vice President Álvaro García Linera, resigned the same day, on live television; both also delivered written resignations.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] In Morales's case, he would later describe in his memoir *Volveremos y seremos millones* (We'll come back and we'll be millions) that he made the decision to resign the night before the requests.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Following his resignation and the resignations of the next two politicians in the line of succession, Jeanine Áñez, second vice-president of the Senate, was next in line for the presidency.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] On 12 November 2019, she formed an interim government.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Protests continued until the end of November, primarily by those who sought Morales' return.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Under direction from Morales and his allies, and at times under coercion, protesters created blockades on inter-departmental highways, resulting in shortages of food and fuel.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The UN High Commissioner for Human Rights expressed concerns over massacres by the new government in response to armed protests at Senkata and Sacaba.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] By 25 November 2019, the interim government had made agreements with most protest leaders to end blockades, and began to withdraw troops and to release arrested protesters.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Article 168 of the 2009 constitution allowed the president and vice-president to be re-elected only once, limiting the number of terms to two.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The governing party, the Movement for Socialism (MAS) sponsored an effort to amend this article.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The referendum was authorized by a joint session of the Plurinational Legislative Assembly on 26 September 2015, by a vote of 112 to 41.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Law 757, which convened the February referendum, passed by 113 votes to 43 and was promulgated on 5 November 2015.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The referendum marked the rise of anti-Morales sentiment in Bolivia.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The vote was held on 21 February 2016 and the proposed amendment was rejected by 51.3% to 48.7%.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] A successful "yes" vote would have allowed President Evo Morales and Vice President Álvaro García Linera to run for another term in office in 2019.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Morales had already been elected three times.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The first time, in 2006, is not counted, as it was before the two-term limit was introduced by the 2009 constitution.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Despite the referendum result, the Plurinational Constitutional Tribunal overruled the constitution by deferring to Article 23 of the American Convention on Human Rights, which promotes the human right to participate in government.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The court ruled a little over one year after the referendum in December 2017 that all public offices would have no term limits, thus allowing Morales to run for a fourth term.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The removal of term limits proved controversial among Bolivians, including Morales' supporters, with some losing trust in Morales for overturning a referendum.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Heading into the elections, some voters distrusted Bolivia's voting system, suspecting fraud after Morales and his supporters disregarded the results of the 2016 referendum.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Bolivia's Plurinational Electoral Body and the private company in charge of the preliminary vote count ad announced eleven days before the election, on 9 October, that only approximately 80% of the preliminary results would be released.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] On 20 October 2019, the first round of voting for all government positions was held.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The Supreme Electoral Tribunal released two sets of counts shortly after the vote was closed.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] First was an exit poll that verified 95.6% of votes that showed incumbent President of Bolivia Evo Morales as having 9.33 percentage points over his main opposition and former president, Carlos Mesa.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Leading by less than 10 percentage points indicates the vote must continue to a second run-off round.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The complete count then appeared as provisional results on a website with routine live updates.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] At the point of 83.8% of votes in the complete count having been verified, the website showed Morales at 45.3% and Mesa at 38.2%; this also reflected a less than ten-point lead.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] However, no further updates to the preliminary results were made after 7:40 pm local time (UTC−4).
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The electoral authorities explained that updates to the preliminary count had been halted because the official results were beginning to be released; nevertheless, no official results were published overnight.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] At 9:25 pm, as the vote counting was still underway, President Morales declared himself the winner of the elections, stating that while he would wait for final scrutiny of the results, the outstanding vote from rural areas would guarantee his victory; he did not mention the possibility of a runoff.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Most of the remaining votes, from remote rural areas, were expected to go in Morales's favour, although the Organization of American States (OAS) recommended a runoff be held even if Morales's lead exceeded 10 points.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Félix Patzi, the presidential candidate for the *Movimiento Tercer Sistema*, alleged that following the unexplained 24-hour pause in the vote count on the day of the election, votes for his party had been changed to votes for the MAS.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] On the day following the election, protests erupted in cities across Bolivia, several of which became violent.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] In La Paz, a clash between opponents and supporters of Morales and police took place; opposition groups were attacked with tear gas by the police.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] In Riberalta, protesters toppled a statue of Hugo Chávez, an ally of Evo Morales, and left its head in front of the mayor's home.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The mayor of Cobija, Luis Gatty Ribeiro, and the governor of Pando, Luis Adolfo Flores, were attacked by protesters, with Flores being hospitalized.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] In Oruro, a MAS tent and a Public Ministry vehicle were destroyed.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The Ponchos Rojos, an indigenous organization and militia, announced that it would hold marches in support of Morales.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] It also warned it might resort to roadblocks in La Paz and would respond to attacks with *chicotes* (whips) and other weapons.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] In Sucre, a group of female police officers marched in the city's central square, calling for calm and demanding that the government refrain from police violence and respect the people's will.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] In Sucre, Potosí and Tarija, several ballot boxes and election-related buildings were set on fire, including the campaign headquarters of MAS and the offices of an indigenous workers organization.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] In Potosí, the electoral court was set on fire, along with several hotels being used as vote counting centers.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Four departmental electoral tribunals suspended their vote counts due to protests occurring outside.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The Chuquisaca Departmental Electoral Court moved its vote count to the town of Zudañez after its facilities in Sucre were burned down.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Likewise, the Electoral Tribunal of Potosí ended the recount in the municipality of Llallagua, without notifying the delegates of the opposition political parties.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The counts show that in the municipalities of Zudañez and Llallagua the government party managed to obtain more than two thirds of the votes.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] In La Paz and Potosí, boxes of electoral ballots were found in trash cans and in private homes, which further fueled the protests.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Protests, strikes and roadblocks continued over the next several weeks, sometimes turning violent.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Police frequently dispersed demonstrations with tear gas.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Luis Fernando Camacho, president of the Civic Committee in Santa Cruz, emerged as a leader of the protests in this time.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Bolivians living abroad also organized demonstrations, demanding a second round between the leading candidates.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] On October 25, the official results were announced, showing 47% for Morales, which would have enabled him to avoid a second round.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] There were reports of people beginning to stockpile food.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Over the next weeks, roadblocks were set up across the country by both supporters and opponents of Morales.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] In some cities the police was mobilized to prevent violence, although reports emerged of officers not protecting both sides.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Opposition protesters in Oruro set fire to the homes of several MAS politicians, including the governors of Oruro and Chuquisaca, and Esther Morales, Evo Morales' sister.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] In the town of Vinto, opposition protesters set the town hall on fire and kidnapped the mayor, Patricia Arce.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Protesters allegedly beat her, cut her hair, and forced her to walk barefoot 40 blocks where they then urinated and spit on her.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] On October 31, the OAS began its audit of the election, with representatives from Spain, Paraguay and Mexico monitoring.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] On the same day, the government announced that at least two people had died in the protests since they began, both in the town of Montero.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] A further fatality occurred on November 7, when a student was killed during a confrontation between supporters and opponents of Morales.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] By November 8, members of the police had joined the anti-Morales protests; in the evening, several could be seen protesting with flags on the roof of the Cochabamba police department, as well as in La Paz, Santa Cruz, and Sucre.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] On November 9, the Bolivian army announced that it would not suppress the protests.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Evo Morales notes in his memoirs that he privately made the decision to resign that evening.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] On 10 November the Organization of American States gave its audit of the election.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The report alleged multiple irregularities, including "manipulations of the I.T. system [that] are of such magnitude that they should be investigated in depth." The organization recommended annulling the election and holding it again with new electoral authorities.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The same day, the military asked Morales to resign and called on the Bolivian people to refrain from violence and disorder.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Approximately an hour later, Morales announced his immediate resignation.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] He fled to Mexico the next day, which had offered him asylum.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The police withdrew from La Paz streets the next day, as crowds welcomed the transfer of power with fireworks.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] There were reports of looting and more politically motivated arson.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] At the same time, protests were held in support of Morales throughout Bolivia.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] El Alto was the site of a particularly large protest, in which multiple people were injured, with crowds chanting, "Now, civil war!" and waving the Wiphala indigenous flag.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The acting president, Jeanine Áñez, called for the military to support the police.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The head of Bolivia's military said that following reports police have been overtaxed by weeks of unrest, the armed forces would provide help in keeping order.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] On November 12, citing article 169 of the Constitution of Bolivia, Jeanine Áñez declared herself President of the Senate, which made her the next in line for the office of the President of Bolivia.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Parliament then voted to make her president.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Although the vote did not have a quorum as it was boycotted by Morales' party, Movement for Socialism, it was later upheld by the Plurinational Constitutional Tribunal.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Protests intensified following Morales' departure, with pro-Morales protesters cutting off major Bolivian roads.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] In La Paz, tens of thousands of pro-Morales protesters clashed with police, military, and opposition forces as they attempted to make their way to the city's centre to protest Morales' removal.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Another march of several thousand people was blocked from reaching the city's main square by military and security forces with tear gas and water cannons.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] In response, pro-Morales protesters blocked roads leading to the city's airport.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Police, military and opposition forces set up roadblocks in anticipation of a renewed march on the city's centre.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The wiphala, a flag representing the indigenous people of the Andes, became a symbol for Morales supporters.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] In some cases, the flag became a point of polarization; a video appeared online showing police officers cutting the flag out of their uniforms.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] On November 13, Bolivian police used tear gas to break up a peaceful pro-Morales protest in La Paz.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Following this, it blocked about a dozen pro-Morales senators from entering the legislature, upon which pro-Morales demonstrators responded with cries of "dictatorship" and by throwing stones at the policemen.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] In Sacaba, nine people were killed and over 100 injured during clashes between security forces and protesters.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] This resulted after police and armed forces attempted to prevent them from marching in either central Sacaba or the city of Cochabamba.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Demonstrators set off sticks of dynamite, while the police and armed forces tried to disperse them with tear gas.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The total death toll since October 20 reached 23, as a demonstrator injured by gunfire died on June 11, 2020, after seven months with a bullet lodged in his head.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Áñez announced that the military would be exempt from criminal responsibility when acting in a "legitimate defense or state of necessity." The Inter-American Commission on Human Rights commission condemned the decree.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Morales described the events as a massacre and the Áñez-led government as a "dictatorship".
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] UN High Commissioner for Human Rights Michelle Bachelet called the events an "extremely dangerous development" and warned that widespread arrests and detentions were adding to the tensions, and that the crisis couldn't be solved through force and repression.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] A UN envoy met with Añez shortly thereafter to relay the organization's "concern".
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Arturo Murillo, a government minister, claimed that the army had not been ordered to fire and implied that the shots came from the side of the protesters.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] He also called for a transparent investigation by the attorney general's office.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] In October 2023, the Attorney General sought criminal charges for eighteen former members of the government and military in part for their roles in the killings, including Áñez and Murillo.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Thousands of Bolivian coca farmers came out in protest in favour of Morales and called for the resignation of Añez as Acting President.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Bolivian police fired tear gas in the country's highlands to prevent the demonstrators from reaching the city of Cochabamba.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Some of the protesters responded to the launching of tear gas by throwing stones at the police officers, which in turn responded by arresting at least ten demonstrators.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Senate president and MAS leader Mónica Eva Copa instructed MAS legislators in the Plurinational Legislative Assembly to cancel a planned vote to reject Morales' resignation.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] She later announced that legislation would be introduced to annul the 20 October election and move towards new elections as soon as possible.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Eight people were killed in clashes outside the major Senkata gasoline plant that had been blockaded for days by Morales supporters as police and military attempted to escort a fuel convoy to relieve shortages in La Paz.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Witnesses said that the men died when a military unit guarding the plant opened fire on the protesters that had surrounded it for over a week.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Bolivia's new defense minister, Fernando López, told reporters that “not one bullet” had been fired by the military at Senkata, an account that was contradicted by dozen of witnesses who had gathered at the church that night.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Dozens of thousands of pro-Morales protesters marched some 15 km from El Alto to downtown La Paz in response to the killings at Senkata.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] They brought with them the coffins of five of the eight victims of the tragedy.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Protesters were dispersed with tear gas, which also hit many passersby.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Police on motorcycles continued to fire tear gas at hiding or retreating protesters, pushing them further from the San Francisco Square.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The Anez-led interim government blamed Morales and "radical groups" of allegedly supporting the violence.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The interim government opened an investigation into Morales for "terrorism and sedition." Hours later, the vice-president of MAS-IPSP was arrested while travelling in a vehicle without licence plates carrying a number of computers and biometric equipment taken from the electoral commission offices.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The suspension of the vote count generated criticism in the opposition and the electoral observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS).
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] In addition, the mission published a statement calling for respect for the will of the citizens.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Carlos Mesa called for civil mobilizations in defense of the vote after denouncing fraud in the elections.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] In a later video, Mesa called for constant protesting until a second round of voting was held, adding that he would bring proof of fraud.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The Bolivian Episcopal Conference (CEB) warned of fraud and demanded that the electoral authorities fulfill their duty as an "impartial arbitrator of the electoral process".
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The Minister of Justice, Héctor Arce, denied the alleged electoral fraud and said that the demonstrations are unjustified, since the electoral calculation process is free and public.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Gunnar Vargas, also member of the electoral board, announced in the radio that he went into hiding for his personal safety.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The National Committee for the Defense of Democracy in Bolivia (Conade) held the Morales government responsible for any confrontation that may arise in the country and called for an indefinite national strike from midnight on the morning of 23 October.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] On Saturday 26 October, after international calls for an audit of the electoral processes, Morales invited foreign governments to hold one, and promised to move the election to a run-off should any fraud be found.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] In the announcement on Friday 8 November, Supreme Electoral Tribunal (TSE) denied that irregularities had taken place in the vote count.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] TSE referred critics to a report by the company Ethical Hacking, which had checked the electronic vote and did not find any kind of "alteration of the data." But the company's chief, Alvaro Andrade, said his firm did find "vulnerabilities" in the vote count.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The Bolivian Football Federation (FBF) suspended all matches on day 17 of the Clausura tournament of the Bolivian Primera División, due to a predicted lack of presence of both players and spectators because of the protests.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The Bolivian Association of Supermarkets announced that the opening hours of supermarkets and hypermarkets for the day of 25 October would be from 7:00 am through noon.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] A correspondent for the Cochabamba newspaper *Los Tiempos*, Wilson Aguilar, said he was assaulted on 21 October by MAS supporters during the Supreme Electoral Tribunal conference in La Paz.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The newspaper *El Deber* reported that on the night of 21 October, Vice Minister of Communication Leyla Medinacelli called the newspaper to "ask for a headline" on the front page of the next day's edition, specifying that it should encourage protesters to "demobilize".
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The newspaper clarified that it does not allow people who are not their own journalists to "impose a headline".
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] On 10 November the newspaper *Página Siete* announced it would not publish its morning edition of 11 November due to security reasons.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The website and social media later resumed its updating.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Two days later on 12 November, the newspaper *El Diario* announced it would not publish its print edition of that day due to security reasons, while the online edition would still be updated.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Following Morales' resignation, a large anti-Morales Twitter bot network was uncovered by the microblogging site in mid November.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The network had published automated tweets which declared opposition to Morales, further adding that the events were "not a coup".
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] Compared to the extremely low proportion of the population that speaks English, the abundance of English tweets from this network suggests that it was intended to sway opinions beyond Bolivia.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The company behind the site had removed many of the tweets by 19 November, but media reports suggested that around 4200 were still up by that point.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The Venezuelan government pro propaganda network Telesur alleged that nearly 70,000 fake accounts had been used by the network, many of which were created days before.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] A Social Networks head working for the Spanish party Podemos further alleged that fake accounts were used to artificially boost the online following of anti-Morales political figures, including Añez.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] On 21 January 2020, the interim government's Department of Justice produced a 65-page document on cases where they believed human rights had been violated.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] This was created with the intention of presenting these cases to be investigated by the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights (IACHR) and to different embassies and international organizations.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] The report is in two parts, with the second relating to events of violence, sedition and terrorism that allegedly occurred since the 20 October elections.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] After the MAS returned to power in the 2020 Bolivian general election, Arce was imprisoned and tried over the killing of demonstrators during the protests and sedition.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2019-bolivian-protests] In 2025, her trial for the killings was annulled by a judge who ruled that she is entitled to a special judicial process for former heads of state handled by the Plurinational Legislative Assembly rather than the regular courts.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2021-junior-pan-american-games] The **2021 Junior Pan American Games** (Spanish: *Juegos Panamericanos Junior 2021*) were the first edition of the Junior Pan American Games, an international multi-sports event for athletes aged 17 to 22 in the Americas, organized by Panam Sports.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2021-junior-pan-american-games] It was held in Cali and Valle, Colombia between November 25 to December 5, 2021.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2021-junior-pan-american-games] The deadline for the presentation of candidacy to organize the first Junior Pan American Games was January 31, 2019, on which date Cali, Santa Ana, and Monterrey were selected as host city candidates by Panam Sports.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2021-junior-pan-american-games] Cali was chosen as the host city by the Executive Committee in San José, Costa Rica on March 27, 2019.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2021-junior-pan-american-games] Colombian Olympic Committee President Baltazar Medina noted that the reason Cali applied to host the games was to open the possibility of Colombia hosting larger multi-sports events, such as the Bolivarian Games and the Central American and Caribbean Games.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2021-junior-pan-american-games] Cali would be the main city for the games, while Palmira, Buga, and Calima El Darién would act as sub-centers.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2021-junior-pan-american-games] Notably, 2021 will be the 50th anniversary of the 1971 Pan American Games, which is the last time that Cali hosted the Pan American Games.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2021-junior-pan-american-games] On January 29, 2019, Mayoress Milena Calderón Sol de Escalón confirmed that Santa Ana would apply to be the host of the inaugural games, stating, "We are preparing all the presentations we have to do before the International Olympic Committee.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2021-junior-pan-american-games] Cali and six other locales (Buga, Yumbo, Jamundí, Calima El Darien, Palmira and Barranquilla) in Colombia will stage the competitions.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2021-junior-pan-american-games] The full sport program was confirmed in September 2020.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2021-junior-pan-american-games] After originally being included, basketball (5x5), BMX freestyle and field hockey were not included on the final list.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2021-junior-pan-american-games] Other Olympic events and disciplines not contested included open water swimming, water polo, canoe slalom, equestrian, football and rugby sevens.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2021-junior-pan-american-games] All 41 nations who are members of the Panam Sports were expected to compete.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2021-junior-pan-american-games] The numbers in parentheses represents the number of athletes qualified.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2024-bolivarian-youth-games] Originally scheduled to be held in Sucre, Bolivia from 17 April to 1 May 2020, the inaugural edition of the Bolivarian Youth Games underwent several postponements until finally held from 4 to 14 April 2024.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2024-bolivarian-youth-games] ODEBO launched the Bolivarian Youth Games for the first time in 2010 with Lima, Peru to be the host city of the first edition in 2015.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2024-bolivarian-youth-games] In February 2015, the event was postponed in order to establish the age limit for athletes as well as the sports program and a new date for the Games.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2024-bolivarian-youth-games] In July 2015, during its Extraordinary General Assembly, ODEBO moved the Games to 2016, keeping Lima as host city.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2024-bolivarian-youth-games] In January 2016, ODEBO approved the age range for athletes following the same criteria as the International Olympic Committee for the Youth Olympic Games, and the Games were moved to 2019.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2024-bolivarian-youth-games] In 2017, the Games were again rescheduled, this time for 2020, and Peru resigned to host the Games, giving way to Sucre, Bolivia being named as the new host city on 10 November 2017.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2024-bolivarian-youth-games] Early 2019, the Games were scheduled to be held between 17 April and 1 May 2020, but were then rescheduled for 17–30 October 2020 due to the 2019 Bolivian protests, and later for 5–18 December 2020 due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2024-bolivarian-youth-games] In October 2021, the Games were postponed to 2022 due to lack of funding and to avoid a clash with the 2021 Junior Pan American Games (25 November–5 December).
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2024-bolivarian-youth-games] In April 2022, ODEBO and Bolivian authorities reactivate the organization of the event, setting April 2023 as the new date for the Games.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2024-bolivarian-youth-games] In August 2022, ODEBO's President Baltazar Medina confirmed the First Bolivarian Youth Games in Sucre from 30 November–9 December 2023 as new tentative dates, which were confirmed in January 2023.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2024-bolivarian-youth-games] Finally, in April 2023, the Games were rescheduled for the last time to take place between 5 and 14 April 2024 in order to allow more time for the organization and to coincide with Sucre's bicentennial commemorative activities.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2024-bolivarian-youth-games] All 7 ODEBO's National Olympic Committees (NOCs) will participate in these games.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2024-bolivarian-youth-games] Each NOC was able to enter a maximum of 200 athletes, with the exception of the host, which was entitled to enter up to 300 athletes.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2024-bolivarian-youth-games] Numbers in brackets denote the number of athletes being sent to the Games.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2024-bolivarian-youth-games] The original 2020 games program proposed 25 sports in 31 disciplines.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/2024-bolivarian-youth-games] The final 2024 program feature 24 sports in 27 disciplines with the following changes regarding the original program: Football and Softball were replaced by Futsal and Baseball5 while Shooting was removed from the program.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] 3x3 has been a basketball format long played in streets and gyms across the world, albeit in a less formal way.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] Starting in the late 2000s, 3x3 game rules started to become standardized throughout the United States, most notably through the Gus Macker and Hoop It Up tournament series, which held large events across the country that included teams and players from all skill levels.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] In 1992, Adidas launched its now-discontinued streetball competition.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] Since then, the number of 3x3 events and competitions has been steadily growing around the world.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] A Romanian organization, Sport Arena Streetball, began hosting 3x3 events in Bucharest as early as 2005, helping to grow the sport locally and regionally before formal FIBA rules were introduced.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] FIBA first test 3x3 at the 2007 Asian Indoor Games in Macau, followed by further test events in April 2008 in the Dominican Republic and October 2008 in Indonesia.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] The international debut of 3x3 under FIBA rules occurred at the 2009 Asian Youth Games, where 19 teams competed in the boys' tournament and 16 teams competed in the girls' tournament, with all games held at Anglican High School in Tanah Merah, Singapore.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] 3x3 made its worldwide competitive debut at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics in Singapore, where 20 teams competed in both boys' and girls' categories, with games held at the Youth Space.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] Since then, FIBA has regularly held world championships in both open and U18 categories.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] Bucharest, later called the "Mecca of 3x3 basketball" by Sports Illustrated, hosted the first FIBA Europe 3x3 Championships in 2014, an event that helped establish organized 3x3 competition across Europe.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] In subsequent years, the city also hosted international 3x3 tournaments, attracting teams from outside Europe.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] FIBA developed 3x3 as a standalone discipline with its own format and regular international competitions.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made its Olympic debut at the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] The 3x3 basketball variation has also been used in several tournaments, such as the Nike 3ON3 Tournament and Spokane Hoopfest, the largest 3x3 basketball tournament in the world, held annually in Spokane, Washington.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] FIBA releases from time-to-time a supplement to its official basketball rules specifically for 3x3.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] The rules state that regular FIBA rules apply to all situations not specifically addressed in the FIBA 3x3 rules.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] The current set, both in an abbreviated version and longer format, was published in August 2019.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] The current rules depart from regular full-court basketball in the following ways.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] Each team consists of three players and one substitute.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] Each team must have three players on the court when the game begins.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] The game is played on a half-court with one basket.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] The American NBA & WNBA standard half-court distance is 15.24 m (50 ft) wide & 14.33 m (47 ft) long.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] The ball is the size of a size 6 basketball (720 mm, 28.5 in) as used in the women's full-court game and its mass is that of the size 7 standard (620 g, 22 oz) used in the men's full-court game.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] A coin toss is held immediately before the game, and the winning team of the coin flip can choose to take possession of the ball at the start of the game, or take the first possession of a potential overtime period.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] In turn, this means that if the game goes into overtime, the first possession goes to the team that started the game on defense.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] The game begins with the defensive team passing the ball to the offensive team to signify the start of the game.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] All offensive players must begin outside of the arc (the opposite side of the arc of the net), and the defensive team must begin inside of the arc.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] Once the offensive team receives the ball, the clock starts.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] This exchange is also used to restart the game from any dead ball situation.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] The game is a single period of a maximum 10 minutes and the winner is the first team to score 21 or the team with the higher score at the end of the 10 minutes; scoring 21 points immediately ends the game.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] Every successful shot inside the arc, including free throws, is awarded one point, while every successful shot outside of the arc ("downtown") is awarded two points.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] After a made goal or free throw (except for technical or unsportsmanlike fouls and team fouls 10 or more; see below), play restarts with a player from the non-scoring team taking the ball directly under the basket and then dribbling or passing it to a point behind the arc.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] The defense is not allowed to play for the ball inside the block/charge semi-circle under the basket.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] In any held-ball situation, the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] The offensive team must attempt a shot for a goal within 12 seconds.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] An offensive player may also not dribble inside the arc with their back or side to the basket for more than 3 consecutive seconds.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] For either violation the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] There is a Trent Tucker Rule in which with up to 0.2 seconds left in regulation or on the shot clock, a high lob, or tip-in must be made.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] A tie in regulation time leads to an untimed overtime period, after a one-minute intermission.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] Whichever team began the game as the defensive team, begins overtime as the offensive team.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] The first team to score two points wins the game.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] Note: if a game is tied at 20 at the end of regulation, a team scoring their 21st point in overtime does not end the game.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] Substitutions can occur only in a dead-ball situation; a substitute can only enter from behind the end line opposite the basket, and the substitution becomes official once the player leaving the game has "tagged up" by making physical contact with the substitute.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] Each team is allowed one 30 second time-out per game.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] Each personal or technical foul counts as one team foul, while each unsportsmanlike or disqualifying foul counts as two team fouls.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] Personal fouls during the act of shooting inside the arc are awarded one free throw, while fouls during the act of shooting behind the arc and the shot is unsuccessful are awarded two free throws.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] Team fouls 7, 8 and 9 are awarded two free throws, and all team fouls thereafter are awarded two free throws and possession of the ball.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] The "bonus" rule specifically supersedes the normal rule for fouls in the act of shooting.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] The un-timed overtime period is considered extension of regulation for purpose of team fouls.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] The first unsportsmanlike foul against a player results in two free throws.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] A second unsportsmanlike foul, or a disqualifying foul, results in two free throws and possession.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] A player who commits two unsportsmanlike fouls is disqualified.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] A team loses the game by default if all of its players are disqualified.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] All technical fouls result in one free throw, with possession going to the team that was entitled to possession at that time.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] If a foul is committed that results in the non-fouling team retaining possession, i.e. a technical or "unsportsmanlike" foul, the non-fouling team will receive the exchange outside of the arc.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] Offensive fouls, if not technical, unsportsmanlike, or disqualifying, never result in free throws, regardless of the number of team fouls.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] In the case of a double foul, no free throws are awarded to either team, regardless of team foul count or whether the double fouls were unsportsmanlike.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] FIBA sees 3x3 as a major vehicle for promotion of the game of basketball throughout the world.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] FIBA Secretary General and IOC member Patrick Baumann explained: "The 3x3 concept has all the elements and skills required for basketball, it has inspired and will continue to inspire many great players in the future.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] At the same time, it is the easiest and one of the most-effective ways to bring youngsters to basketball, keep them and promote our game.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] FIBA is pursuing a strategy to implement 3x3.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] FIBA has developed a digital community that acts as a repository for all FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events worldwide and offers all players an individual world ranking based on the points earned by players at FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] Any event around the world can become FIBA-endorsed by using FIBA's freeware, EventMaker, to organise the event.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] All FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events are classified within an established competition hierarchy, thus forming an official competition network.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] The pinnacle of this competition network is the FIBA 3x3 World Tour, which includes a series of World Tour Masters and one Final.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] A team can qualify for a World Tour Masters by playing in any of the designated World Tour qualifiers.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] The North American National Basketball Association (NBA) has also embraced 3x3.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] Since 2016, the NBA has held a summer series of tournaments known as "Dew NBA 3X", where local amateur players from around the US compete in regional events for cash prizes and a finals berth.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] The men's and women's NBA 3X champions then advance to the USA Basketball national 3x3 championship to potentially represent their country internationally.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] These tournaments also include live music performances, 3-point shooting contests for fans, an *NBA 2K* eSports competition, and appearances from current NBA players.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] The qualification system for the FIBA 3x3 World Cups for men and women differs radically from the system used for FIBA full-court competitions.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] According to *The New York Times*, 3x3 has "an unusual qualifying system designed to grow the sport all year long as much as find the best teams for the World Cup." National team entries are based strictly on a country's official 3x3 ranking.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] The ranking system for national teams also considers individual player rankings.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] For example, the US women's team qualified for the 2018 World Cup while the men's team did not, even though the men were ranked higher than the women on the cutoff date.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] Participating in a FIBA-sanctioned 3x3 event can earn ranking points; according to a FIBA executive, "Andorra has heavy participation every weekend." The current concentration of ranking events in Europe makes it more difficult for non-European nations, especially the US, to qualify.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] The aforementioned FIBA executive, when asked about the prospect of the 2020 Olympic debut of 3x3 potentially lacking any participation from the US, admitted that "a lot of teams want to beat the US.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] After the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics, FIBA established a regular World Cup that always includes men and women competing simultaneously in open, U23 and U18 categories.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] World Cups are played every year, except in years when there are Youth Olympic Games or Olympic Games.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] The COVID-19 pandemic caused the cancellation of the 2020 event.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] Classification to the World Cup is based on the 3x3 Federation Ranking, which ranks all National Federations based on the 3x3 Individual World Ranking points of their top 100 nationals in the respective category (i.e. men, women, U23 men, U23 women, U18 men, and U18 women).
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball became a regular European Games contest since its introduction at the 2015 European Games in Baku, Azerbaijan.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made a debut in Olympic programme for the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo, Japan, for both men and women.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball was included in 2022 Commonwealth Games in Birmingham, England.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/3x3-basketball] After the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, FIBA banned Russian teams and officials from participating in FIBA 3x3 Basketball competitions.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/andina-news-agency] Andina was founded on June 12, 1981, during the second presidency of Fernando Belaúnde Terry.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/andina-news-agency] It is an official state outlet of the Peruvian government, part of the group Editora Perú, which also publishes the daily newspaper El Peruano.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/andina-news-agency] The two outlets were briefly combined in 2001, before Alejandro Toledo's government reestablished Andina as a separate news agency the following year, under the leadership of the journalist Gerardo Barraza.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/andina-news-agency] The agency, which has correspondents in every province of the country, sends more than 90 dispatches a day, on average, to 69 radio stations, 40 local and national newspapers, and four international news agencies.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/andina-news-agency] It also contributes relevant news bulletins to Bolivian outlets.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/andina-news-agency] Since 2012, Andina has been a member of the Latin American Union of News Agencies.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The oldest known evidence of arrows (not found with surviving bows) comes from South African sites such as Sibudu Cave, where the remains of bone and stone arrowheads have been found dating approximately 72,000 to 60,000 years ago.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] However, the earliest remains of complete bows and arrows are found in Northern Europe.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] These include the evidence found at Mannheim-Vogelstang, in modern-day Germany, dated 17,500 to 18,000 years ago, and also at Stellmoor dated 11,000 years ago.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Azilian points found in Grotte du Bichon, Switzerland, alongside the remains of both a bear and a hunter, with flint fragments found in the bear's third vertebra, suggest the use of arrows at 13,500 years ago.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Other signs of its use in Europe come from the Stellmoor in the Ahrensburg valley north of Hamburg, Germany and dates from the late Paleolithic, about 10,000–9000 BC.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The arrows were made of pine and consisted of a main shaft and a 15–20 cm (5.9–7.9 in) fore shaft with a flint point.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] There are no definite earlier bows; previous pointed shafts are known, but may have been launched by spear-throwers rather than bows.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The oldest bows known so far comes from the Holmegård swamp in Denmark.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] At the site of Nataruk in Turkana County, Kenya, obsidian bladelets found embedded in a skull and within the thoracic cavity of another skeleton, suggest the use of stone-tipped arrows as weapons about 10,000 years ago.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Bows eventually replaced the spear-thrower as the predominant means for launching shafted projectiles, on every continent except Australasia, though spear-throwers persisted alongside the bow in parts of the Americas, including Mexico and among the Inuit.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Bows and arrows have been present in Egyptian and neighbouring Nubian culture since its respective predynastic and Pre-Kerma origins.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] In the Levant, artifacts that could be arrow-shaft straighteners are known from the Natufian culture, (c.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Classical civilizations, notably the Babylonians, Assyrians, Greeks, Armenians, Persians, Parthians, Romans, Indians, Koreans, Chinese, and Japanese fielded large numbers of archers in their armies.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Akkadians were the first to use composite bows in war according to the victory stele of Naram-Sin of Akkad.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Egyptians referred to Nubia as "Ta-Seti," or "The Land of the Bow," since the Nubians were known to be expert archers, and by the 16th Century BC Egyptians were using the composite bow in warfare.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The Bronze Age Aegean Cultures were able to deploy a number of state-owned specialized bow makers for warfare and hunting purposes already from the 15th century BC.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The Welsh longbow proved its worth for the first time in Continental warfare at the Battle of Crécy.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] In the Americas archery was widespread at European contact.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The composite bow was likely invented in central Asia, with the Scythians being the likely inventors of the first composite bows.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The Sanskrit term for archery, dhanurvidya, came to refer to martial arts in general.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] In East Asia, Goguryeo, one of the Three Kingdoms of Korea was well known for its regiments of exceptionally skilled archers.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The medieval shortbow was technically identical with the classical era bows, having a range of approximately 91 m (299 ft).
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] It was the primary ranged weapon of the battlefield through the early medieval period.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Around the tenth century the crossbow was introduced in Europe.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Crossbows generally had a longer range, greater accuracy and more penetration than the shortbow, but suffered from a much slower rate of fire.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Crossbows were used in the early Crusades, with models having a range of 274 m (899 ft) and being able to penetrate armour or kill a horse.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] During the late medieval period the English army famously relied on massed archers armed with the longbow.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The French army relied more on the crossbow.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Like their predecessors archers were more likely to be peasants or yeomen than men-at-arms.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The longbow had a range of up to 270 m (890 ft).
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] However its lack of accuracy at long ranges made it a mass weapon rather than an individual one.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Significant victories attributable to the longbow, such as the Battle of Crecy and Battle of Agincourt resulted in the English longbow becoming part of military lore.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The Scythians became extremely adept at archery on horseback, and may have invented the first true composite bow, which they spread across Europe and Asia.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Lightly armoured, but highly mobile archers were excellently suited to warfare in the Central Asian steppes, and they formed a large part of armies that repeatedly conquered large areas of Eurasia.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Shorter bows are more suited to use on horseback, and the composite bow enabled mounted archers to use powerful weapons.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Seljuk Turks used mounted archers against the European First Crusade, especially at the Battle of Dorylaeum (1097).
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] One of their tactics was to shoot at the enemy infantry, and use their superior mobility to prevent the enemy from closing with them.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Empires throughout the Eurasian landmass often strongly associated their respective "barbarian" counterparts with the usage of the bow and arrow, to the point where powerful states like the Han dynasty referred to their neighbours, the Xiong-nu, as "Those Who Draw the Bow".
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] For example, Xiong-nu mounted bowmen made them more than a match for the Han military.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] It is possible that "barbarian" peoples were responsible for introducing archery or certain types of bows to their "civilized" counterparts.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Native Americans developed a culture of horseback archery after the introduction of the horse by European explorers in the second millennium.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The development of firearms rendered the bow and arrow obsolete in warfare, although efforts were sometimes made to preserve archery practice.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] In England and Wales, for example, the government tried to enforce practice with the longbow until the end of the 16th century.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] This was because it was recognized that the bow had been instrumental to military success during the Hundred Years' War.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Despite the high social status, ongoing utility, and widespread pleasure of archery in Armenia, China, Egypt, England and Wales, the Americas, India, Japan, Korea, Turkey and elsewhere, almost every culture that gained access to even early firearms used them widely, to the neglect of archery.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Early firearms were inferior in rate-of-fire, and were very sensitive to wet weather.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] However, they had longer effective range and were tactically superior in the common situation of soldiers shooting at each other from behind obstructions.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] They also required significantly less training to use properly, in particular penetrating steel armor without any need to develop special musculature.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Armies equipped with guns could thus provide superior firepower, and highly trained archers became obsolete on the battlefield.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] However, the bow and arrow is still an effective weapon, and archers have seen military action in the 21st century.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Traditional archery remains in use for sport, and for hunting in many areas.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Early recreational archery societies in England included the Finsbury Archers and the Ancient Society of Kilwinning Archers.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The latter's annual Papingo event was first recorded in 1483.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] (In this event, archers shoot vertically from the base of an abbey tower to dislodge a wood pigeon placed approximately 30 m (98 ft) above.) The Royal Company of Archers was formed in 1676 and is one of the oldest sporting bodies in the world.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Archery remained a small and scattered pastime, however, until the late 18th century when it experienced a fashionable revival among the aristocracy.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Sir Ashton Lever, an antiquarian and collector, formed the Toxophilite Society in London in 1781, with the patronage of George, the Prince of Wales.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Archery societies were set up across the country, each with its own strict entry criteria and outlandish costumes.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Recreational archery soon became extravagant social and ceremonial events for the nobility, complete with flags, music and 21-gun salutes for the competitors.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The clubs were "the drawing rooms of the great country houses placed outside" and thus came to play an important role in the social networks of the local upper class.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] As well as its emphasis on display and status, the sport was notable for its popularity with females.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Young women could not only compete in the contests but retain and show off their sexuality while doing so.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Thus, archery came to act as a forum for introductions, flirtation and romance.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] It was often consciously styled in the manner of a Medieval tournament with titles and laurel wreaths being presented as a reward to the victor.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] General meetings were held from 1789, in which local lodges convened together to standardise the rules and ceremonies.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Archery was also co-opted as a distinctively British tradition, dating back to the lore of Robin Hood and it served as a patriotic form of entertainment at a time of political tension in Europe.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The societies were also elitist, and the new middle class bourgeoisie were excluded from the clubs due to their lack of social status.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] After the Napoleonic Wars, the sport became increasingly popular among all classes, and it was framed as a nostalgic reimagining of the preindustrial rural Britain.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Particularly influential was Sir Walter Scott's 1819 novel, *Ivanhoe* that depicted the heroic character Lockseley winning an archery tournament.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The 1840s saw the second attempts at turning the recreation into a modern sport.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Ford helped to improve archery standards and pioneered new archery techniques.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] He won the Grand National 11 times in a row and published a highly influential guide to the sport in 1856.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Towards the end of the 19th century, the sport experienced declining participation as alternative sports such as croquet and tennis became more popular among the middle class.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] By 1889, just 50 archery clubs were left in Britain, but it was still included as a sport at the 1900 Paris Olympics.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The National Archery Association of the United States was organized in 1879, in part by Maurice Thompson (the author of the seminal text "The Witchery of Archery") and his brother Will Thompson.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Maurice was president in its inaugural year and Will was president in 1882, 1903, and 1904.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The 1910 President was Frank E Canfield.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Today it is known as USA Archery and is recognized by United States Olympic & Paralympic Committee.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] In the United States, primitive archery was revived in the early 20th century.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The last of the Yahi Indian tribe, a native known as Ishi, came out of hiding in California in 1911.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] His doctor, Saxton Pope, learned many of Ishi's traditional archery skills, and popularized them.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The Pope and Young Club, founded in 1961 and named in honor of Pope and his friend, Arthur Young, became one of North America's leading bowhunting and conservation organizations.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Founded as a nonprofit scientific organization, the Club was patterned after the prestigious Boone and Crockett Club and advocated responsible bowhunting by promoting quality, fair chase hunting, and sound conservation practices.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] From the 1920s, professional engineers took an interest in archery, previously the exclusive field of traditional craft experts.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] They led the commercial development of new forms of bow including the modern recurve and compound bow.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] These modern forms are now dominant in modern Western archery; traditional bows are in a minority.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Archery returned to the Olympics in 1972.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] In the 1980s, the skills of traditional archery were revived by American enthusiasts, and combined with the new scientific understanding.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Much of this expertise is available in the *Traditional Bowyer's Bibles* (see Further reading).
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Modern game archery owes much of its success to Fred Bear, an American bow hunter and bow manufacturer.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Deities and heroes in several mythologies are described as archers, including the Greek Artemis and Apollo, the Roman Diana and Cupid, the Germanic Agilaz, continuing in legends like those of Wilhelm Tell, Palnetoke, or Robin Hood.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Armenian Hayk and Babylonian Marduk, Indian Karna (also known as Radheya/son of Radha), Abhimanyu, Eklavya, Arjuna, Bhishma, Drona, Rama, and Shiva were known for their shooting skills.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The famous archery competition of hitting the eye of a rotating fish while watching its reflection in the water bowl was one of the many archery skills depicted in the *Mahabharata*.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Earlier Greek representations of Heracles normally depict him as an archer.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Three of the Hyperborean Maidens were worshipped on the Greek island of Delos as attendants of Artemis, presiding over aspects of archery; *Hekaerge* (Ἑκαέργη), represented distancing, *Loxo* (Λοξώ), trajectory, and *Oupis* (Οὖπις), aim.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Yi the archer and his apprentice Feng Meng appear in several early Chinese myths, and the historical character of Zhou Tong features in many fictional forms.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Jumong, the first Taewang of the Goguryeo kingdom of the Three Kingdoms of Korea, is claimed by legend to have been a near-godlike archer.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Archery features in the story of Oguz Khagan.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Similarly, archery and the bow feature heavily into historical Korean identity.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] In West African Yoruba belief, Osoosi is one of several deities of the hunt who are identified with bow and arrow iconography and other insignia associated with archery.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] While there is great variety in the construction details of bows (both historical and modern), all bows consist of a string attached to elastic limbs that store mechanical energy imparted by the user drawing the string.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Bows may be broadly split into two categories: those drawn by pulling the string directly and those that use a mechanism to pull the string.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Directly drawn bows may be further divided based upon differences in the method of limb construction, notable examples being self bows, laminated bows and composite bows.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Bows can also be classified by the bow shape of the limbs when unstrung; in contrast to traditional European straight bows, a recurve bow and some types of longbow have tips that curve away from the archer when the bow is unstrung.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The cross-section of the limb also varies; the classic longbow is a tall bow with narrow limbs that are D-shaped in cross section, and the flatbow has flat wide limbs that are approximately rectangular in cross-section.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Cable-backed bows use cords as the back of the bow; the draw weight of the bow can be adjusted by changing the tension of the cable.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] They were widespread among Inuit who lacked easy access to good bow wood.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] One variety of cable-backed bow is the Penobscot bow or Wabenaki bow, invented by Frank Loring (Chief Big Thunder) about 1900.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] It consists of a small bow attached by cables on the back of a larger main bow.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] In different cultures, the arrows are released from either the left or right side of the bow, and this affects the hand grip and position of the bow.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] In Arab archery, Turkish archery, and Japanese archery.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The arrows are released from the right hand side of the bow, and this affects construction of the bow.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] In western archery, the arrow is usually released from the left hand side of the bow for a right-handed archer.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Compound bows are designed to reduce the force required to hold the string at full draw, hence allowing the archer more time to aim with less muscular stress.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Most compound designs use cams or elliptical wheels on the ends of the limbs to achieve this.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] A typical let-off is anywhere from 65% to 80%.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] For example, a 27 kg (60 lb) bow with 80% let-off only requires 53 N (12 lbf) to hold at full draw.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The compound bow was invented by Holless Wilbur Allen in the 1960s (a US patent was filed in 1966 and granted in 1969) and it has become the most widely used type of bow for all forms of archery in North America.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Mechanically drawn bows typically have a stock or other mounting, such as the crossbow.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Crossbows typically have shorter draw lengths compared to compound bows.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Because of this, heavier draw weights are required to achieve the same energy transfer to the arrow.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] These mechanically drawn bows also have devices to hold the tension when the bow is fully drawn.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] They are not limited by the strength of a single archer and larger varieties have been used as siege engines.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The most common form of arrow consists of a shaft, with an arrowhead at the front end, and fletchings and a nock at the other end.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Arrows across time and history have normally been carried in a container known as a quiver, which can take many different forms.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Shafts of arrows are typically composed of solid wood, bamboo, fiberglass, aluminium alloy, carbon fiber, or composite materials.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Fiberglass arrows are brittle, but can be produced to uniform specifications easily.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Aluminium shafts were a very popular high-performance choice in the latter half of the 20th century, due to their straightness, lighter weight, and subsequently higher speed and flatter trajectories.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Carbon fiber arrows became popular in the 1990s because they are very light, flying even faster and flatter than aluminium arrows.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Today, the most popular arrows at tournaments and Olympic events are made of composite materials.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The arrowhead is the primary functional component of the arrow.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Some arrows may simply use a sharpened tip of the solid shaft, but separate arrowheads are far more common, usually made from metal, stone, or other hard materials.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The most commonly used forms are target points, field points, and broadheads, although there are also other types, such as bodkin, judo, and blunt heads.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Fletching is traditionally made from bird feathers, but solid plastic vanes and thin sheet-like spin vanes are used.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] They are attached near the nock (rear) end of the arrow with thin double sided tape, glue, or, traditionally, sinew.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The most common configuration in all cultures is three fletches, though as many as six have been used.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] When the arrow is *three-fletched*, the fletches are equally spaced around the shaft, with one placed such that it is perpendicular to the bow when nocked on the string, though variations are seen with modern equipment, especially when using the modern spin vanes.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] This fletch is called the "index fletch" or "cock feather" (also known as "the odd vane out" or "the nocking vane"), and the others are sometimes called the "hen feathers".
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Commonly, the cock feather is of a different color.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] However, if archers are using fletching made of feather or similar material, they may use same color vanes, as different dyes can give varying stiffness to vanes, resulting in less precision.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] When an arrow is *four-fletched*, two opposing fletches are often cock feathers, and occasionally the fletches are not evenly spaced.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The fletching may be either *parabolic* cut (short feathers in a smooth parabolic curve) or *shield* cut (generally shaped like half of a narrow shield), and is often attached at an angle, known as *helical* fletching, to introduce a stabilizing spin to the arrow while in flight.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Whether helical or straight fletched, when natural fletching (bird feathers) is used it is critical that all feathers come from the same side of the bird.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Oversized fletchings can be used to accentuate drag and thus limit the range of the arrow significantly; these arrows are called *flu-flus*.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Misplacement of fletchings can change the arrow's flight path dramatically.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Dacron and other modern materials offer high strength for their weight and are used on most modern bows.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Linen and other traditional materials are still used on traditional bows.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Several modern methods of making a bowstring exist, such as the 'endless loop' and 'Flemish twist'.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Almost any fiber can be made into a bowstring.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The author of *Arab Archery* suggests the hide of a young, emaciated camel.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Njál's saga describes the refusal of a wife, Hallgerður, to cut her hair to make an emergency bowstring for her husband, Gunnar Hámundarson, who is then killed.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Most modern archers wear a bracer (also known as an arm-guard) to protect the inside of the bow arm from being hit by the string and prevent clothing from catching the bowstring.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The bracer does not brace the arm; the word comes from the armoury term "brassard", meaning an armoured sleeve or badge.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The Navajo people have developed highly ornamented bracers as non-functional items of adornment.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Some archers (nearly all female archers) wear protection on their chests, called chestguards or plastrons.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The myth of the Amazons was that they had one breast removed to solve this problem.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Roger Ascham mentions one archer, presumably with an unusual shooting style, who wore a leather guard for his face.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The drawing digits are normally protected by a leather tab, glove, or thumb ring.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] A simple tab of leather is commonly used, as is a skeleton glove.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Medieval Europeans probably used a complete leather glove.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Eurasiatic archers who used the thumb or Mongolian draw protected their thumbs, usually with leather according to the author of *Arab Archery*, but also with special rings of various hard materials.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Many surviving Turkish and Chinese examples are works of considerable art.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Some are so highly ornamented that the users could not have used them to loose an arrow.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Possibly these were items of personal adornment, and hence value, remaining extant whilst leather had virtually no intrinsic value and would also deteriorate with time.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] In traditional Japanese archery a special glove is used that has a ridge to assist in drawing the string.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] A release aid is a mechanical device designed to give a crisp and precise loose of arrows from a compound bow.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] In the most commonly used, the string is released by a finger-operated trigger mechanism, held in the archer's hand or attached to their wrist.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] In another type, known as a back-tension release, the string is automatically released when drawn to a pre-determined tension.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Stabilizers are mounted at various points on the bow.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Common with competitive archery equipment are special brackets that allow multiple stabilizers to be mounted at various angles to fine tune the bow's balance.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Stabilizers aid in aiming by improving the balance of the bow.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Sights, quivers, rests, and design of the riser (the central, non-bending part of the bow) make one side of the bow heavier.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] One purpose of stabilizers are to offset these forces.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] A reflex riser design will cause the top limb to lean towards the shooter.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] In this case a heavier front stabilizer is desired to offset this action.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] A deflex riser design has the opposite effect and a lighter front stabilizer may be used.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Stabilizers can reduce noise and vibration.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] These energies are absorbed by viscoelastic polymers, gels, powders, and other materials used to build stabilizers.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Stabilizers improve the forgiveness and accuracy by increasing the moment of inertia of the bow to resist movement during the shooting process.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Lightweight carbon stabilizers with weighted ends are desirable because they improve the moment of inertia while minimizing the weight added.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The standard convention on teaching archery is to hold the bow depending upon eye dominance.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] (One exception is in modern kyūdō where all archers are trained to hold the bow in the left hand.) Therefore, if one is right-eye dominant, they would hold the bow in the left hand and draw the string with the right hand.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] However, not everyone agrees with this line of thought.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] A smoother, and more fluid release of the string will produce the most consistently repeatable shots, and therefore may provide greater accuracy of the arrow flight.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Some believe that the hand with the greatest dexterity should therefore be the hand that draws and releases the string.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Either eye can be used for aiming, and the less dominant eye can be trained over time to become more effective for use.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] To assist with this, an eye patch can be temporarily worn over the dominant eye.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The hand that holds the bow is referred to as the *bow hand* and its arm the *bow arm*.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The opposite hand is called the *drawing hand* or *string hand*.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Terms such as *bow shoulder* or *string elbow* follow the same convention.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] If shooting according to eye dominance, right-eye-dominant archers shooting conventionally hold the bow with their left hand.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] If shooting according to hand dexterity, the archer draws the string with the hand that possesses the greatest dexterity, regardless of eye dominance.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] In modern target archery, the standard shooting stance positions the archer's body at or nearly perpendicular to the target and the shooting line, with feet placed approximately shoulder-width apart.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] This is commonly referred to as a "neutral stance".
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] More experienced archers may adopt variations such as an "open stance" (front foot angled toward the target) or "closed stance" (front foot angled away), depending on the individual preference and shooting style.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] To load, the bow is pointed toward the ground, tipped slightly clockwise of vertical (for a right handed shooter) and the shaft of the arrow is placed on the arrow rest or shelf.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The back of the arrow is attached to the bowstring with the **nock** (a small locking groove located at the proximal end of the arrow).
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] This step is called "nocking the arrow".
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Typical arrows with three vanes should be oriented such that a single vane, the "cock feather", is pointing away from the bow, to improve the clearance of the arrow as it passes the arrow rest.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] A compound bow is fitted with a special type of arrow rest, known as a launcher, and the arrow is usually loaded with the cock feather/vane pointed either up, or down, depending upon the type of launcher being used.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The bowstring and arrow are held with three fingers, or with a mechanical arrow release.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Most commonly, for finger shooters, the index finger is placed above the arrow and the next two fingers below, although several other techniques have their adherents around the world, involving three fingers below the arrow, or an arrow pinching technique.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Instinctive shooting is a technique eschewing sights and is often preferred by traditional archers (shooters of longbows and recurves).
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] In either the split finger or three finger under case, the string is usually placed in the first or second joint, or else on the pads of the fingers.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] When using a mechanical release aid, the release is hooked onto the D-loop.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Another type of string hold, used on traditional bows, is the type favoured by the Mongol warriors, known as the "thumb release", style.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] This involves using the thumb to draw the string, with the fingers curling around the thumb to add some support.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] To release the string, the fingers are opened out and the thumb relaxes to allow the string to slide off the thumb.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] When using this type of release, the arrow should rest on the same side of the bow as the drawing hand i.e.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Left hand draw = arrow on left side of bow.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The archer then raises the bow and draws the string, with varying alignments for vertical versus slightly canted bow positions.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] This is often one fluid motion for shooters of recurves and longbows, which tend to vary from archer to archer.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Compound shooters often experience a slight jerk during the drawback, at around the last 4 cm (1.6 in), where the draw weight is at its maximum—before relaxing into a comfortable stable full draw position.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The archer draws the string hand towards the face, where it should rest lightly at a fixed *anchor point*.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] This point is consistent from shot to shot, and is usually at the corner of the mouth, on the chin, to the cheek, or to the ear, depending on preferred shooting style.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The archer holds the bow arm outwards, toward the target.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The elbow of this arm should be rotated so that the inner elbow is perpendicular to the ground, though archers with hyper extendable elbows tend to angle the inner elbow toward the ground, as exemplified by the Korean archer Jang Yong-Ho.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] This keeps the forearm out of the way of the bowstring.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] In modern form, the archer stands erect, forming a "T".
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The archer's lower trapezius muscles are used to pull the arrow to the anchor point.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Some modern recurve bows are equipped with a mechanical device, called a clicker, which produces a clicking sound when the archer reaches the correct draw length.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Traditional English Longbow shooters step "into the bow", exerting force with both the bow arm and the string hand arm simultaneously, especially when using bows having draw weights from 45 kg (99 lb) to over 80 kg (180 lb).
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Heavily stacked traditional bows (recurves, long bows, and the like) are released immediately upon reaching full draw at maximum weight, whereas compound bows reach their maximum weight around the last 4 cm (1.6 in), dropping holding weight significantly at full draw.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Compound bows are often held at full draw for a short time to achieve maximum accuracy.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The arrow is typically released by relaxing the fingers of the drawing hand (see bow draw), or triggering the mechanical release aid.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Usually the release aims to keep the drawing arm rigid, the bow hand relaxed, and the arrow is moved back using the back muscles, as opposed to using just arm motions.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] An archer should also pay attention to the recoil or *follow through* of his or her body, as it may indicate problems with form (technique) that affect accuracy.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] There are two main forms of aiming in archery: using a mechanical or fixed sight, or barebow.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Mechanical sights can be affixed to the bow to aid in aiming.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] They can be as simple as a pin, or may use optics with magnification.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Modern compound bows usually also have a peep sight (rear sight) built into the string, which aids in a consistent anchor point, but this is not allowed for other bow types under World Archery.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Modern compound bows automatically limit the draw length to give a consistent arrow velocity, while traditional bows allow great variation in draw length.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Some bows use mechanical methods to make the draw length consistent.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Barebow archers often use a sight picture, which includes the target, the bow, the hand, the arrow shaft and the arrow tip, as seen at the same time by the archer.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] With a fixed "anchor point" (where the string is brought to, or close to, the face), and a fully extended bow arm, successive shots taken with the sight picture in the same position fall on the same point.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] This lets the archer adjust aim with successive shots to achieve accuracy.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Modern archery equipment usually includes sights.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Instinctive aiming is used by many archers who use traditional bows.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The two most common forms of a non-mechanical release are split-finger and three-under.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Split-finger aiming requires the archer to place the index finger above the nocked arrow, while the middle and ring fingers are both placed below.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Three-under aiming places the index, middle, and ring fingers under the nocked arrow.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] This technique allows the archer to better look down the arrow since the back of the arrow is closer to the dominant eye, and is commonly called "gun barreling" (referring to common aiming techniques used with firearms).
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] When using short bows or shooting from horseback, it is difficult to use the sight picture.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The archer may look at the target, but without including the weapon in the field of accurate view.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Aiming then involves hand-eye coordination—which includes proprioception and motor-muscle memory, similar to that used when throwing a ball.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] With sufficient practice, such archers can normally achieve good practical accuracy for hunting or for war.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Aiming without a sight picture may allow more rapid shooting, not however increasing accuracy.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Instinctive shooting is a style of shooting that includes the barebow aiming method that relies heavily upon the subconscious mind, proprioception, and motor/muscle memory to make aiming adjustments; the term used to refer to a general category of archers who did not use a mechanical or fixed sight.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Gap shooting is an aiming method used by instinctive shooters.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] It involves consciously focusing on the tip of the arrow while maintaining awareness of the target.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The archer must adjust the arrow's trajectory by gauging the distance between the arrow tip and the target, ensuring accurate shots.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] When a projectile is thrown by hand, the speed of the projectile is determined by the kinetic energy imparted by the thrower's muscles performing work.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] However, the energy must be imparted over a limited distance (determined by arm length) and therefore (because the projectile is accelerating) over a limited time.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] As such, the limiting factor is not work but rather power, which determines how much energy can be added in the limited time available.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] When a bow is used, the muscles are able to perform work much more slowly, resulting in greater force and greater work done.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] This work is stored in the bow as elastic potential energy, and when the bowstring is released, this stored energy is imparted to the arrow much more quickly than can be delivered by the muscles, resulting in much higher velocity and, hence, greater distance.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] This same process is employed by frogs, which use elastic tendons to increase jumping distance.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] In archery, some energy dissipates through elastic hysteresis, reducing the overall amount released when the bow is shot.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Of the remaining energy, some is dampened both by the limbs of the bow and the bowstring.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Depending on the arrow's elasticity, some of the energy is also absorbed by compressing the arrow, primarily because the release of the bowstring is rarely in line with the arrow shaft, causing it to flex out to one side.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] This is because the bowstring accelerates faster than the archer's fingers can open, and consequently some sideways motion is imparted to the string, and hence arrow nock, as the power and speed of the bow pulls the string off the opening fingers.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Even with a release aid mechanism some of this effect is usually experienced, since the string always accelerates faster than the retaining part of the mechanism.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] This makes the arrow oscillate in flight—its center flexing to one side and then the other repeatedly, gradually reducing as the arrow's flight proceeds.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] This is clearly visible in high-speed photography of arrows at discharge.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] A direct effect of these energy transfers can clearly be seen when dry firing.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Dry firing refers to releasing the bowstring without a nocked arrow.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Because there is no arrow to receive the stored potential energy, almost all the energy stays in the bow.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Some have suggested that dry firing may cause physical damage to the bow, such as cracks and fractures—and because most bows are not specifically made to handle the high amounts of energy dry firing produces, should never be done.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Modern arrows are made to a specified 'spine', or stiffness rating, to maintain matched flexing and hence accuracy of aim.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] This flexing can be a desirable feature, since, when the spine of the shaft is matched to the acceleration of the bow(string), the arrow bends or flexes around the bow and any arrow-rest, and consequently the arrow, and fletchings, have an un-impeded flight.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] This feature is known as the archer's paradox.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] It maintains accuracy, for if part of the arrow struck a glancing blow on a part of the bow during discharge, some inconsistency would be present, and the excellent accuracy of modern equipment would not be achieved.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The accurate flight of an arrow depends on its fletchings.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The arrow's manufacturer (a "fletcher") can arrange fletching to cause the arrow to rotate along its axis.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] This improves accuracy by evening pressure buildups that would otherwise cause the arrow to "plane" on the air in a random direction after shooting.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Even with a carefully made arrow, the slightest imperfection or air movement causes some unbalanced turbulence in air flow.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Consequently, rotation creates an equalization of such turbulence, which, overall, maintains the intended direction of flight i.e. accuracy.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] This rotation is not to be confused with the rapid gyroscopic rotation of a rifle bullet.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Fletching that is not arranged to induce rotation still improves accuracy by causing a restoring drag any time the arrow tilts from its intended direction of travel.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The innovative aspect of the invention of the bow and arrow was the amount of power delivered to an extremely small area by the arrow.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The huge ratio of length vs. cross sectional area, coupled with velocity, made the arrow more powerful than any other hand held weapon until firearms were invented.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Arrows can spread or concentrate force, depending on the application.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Practice arrows, for instance, have a blunt tip that spreads the force over a wider area to reduce the risk of injury or limit penetration.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Arrows designed to pierce armor in the Middle Ages used a very narrow and sharp tip ("bodkinhead") to concentrate the force.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Arrows used for hunting used a narrow tip ("broadhead") that widens further, to facilitate both penetration and a large wound.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Using archery to take game animals is known as "bow hunting".
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Bow hunting differs markedly from hunting with firearms, as distance between hunter and prey must be much shorter to ensure a humane kill.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] The skills and practices of bow hunting therefore emphasize very close approach to the prey, whether by still hunting, stalking, or waiting in a blind or tree stand.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] In many countries, including much of the United States, bow hunting for large and small game is legal.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Bow hunters generally enjoy longer seasons than are allowed with other forms of hunting such as black powder, shotgun, or rifle.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Usually, compound bows are used for large game hunting due to the relatively short time it takes to master them as opposed to the longbow or recurve bow.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] These compound bows may feature fiber optic sights, stabilizers, and other accessories designed to increase accuracy at longer distances.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Using a bow and arrow to take fish is known as "bow fishing".
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Competitive archery involves shooting arrows at a target for accuracy from a set distance or distances.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] This is the most popular form of competitive archery worldwide and is called target archery.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] A form particularly popular in Europe and America is field archery or 3D Archery, shot at targets generally set at various distances in a wooded setting.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Competitive archery in the United States is governed by USA Archery and National Field Archery Association (NFAA), which also certifies instructors.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] Para-archery is an adaptation of archery for athletes with a disability, governed by the World Archery (WA) and is one of the sports in the Summer Paralympic Games.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/archery] There are also several other lesser-known and historical forms of archery, as well as archery novelty games and flight archery, where the aim is to shoot the greatest distance.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The gymnastic system was mentioned in writings by ancient authors, including Homer, Aristotle, and Plato.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] It included many disciplines that later became independent sports, such as swimming, racing, wrestling, boxing, and horse riding.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Gymnastics evolved in Bohemia and what later became Germany at the beginning of the 19th century.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The term "artistic gymnastics" was introduced to distinguish freestyle performances from those used by the military.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The German educator Friedrich Ludwig Jahn, who was known as the father of gymnastics, invented several apparatus, including the horizontal bar and parallel bars.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Two of the first gymnastics clubs were Turnvereins and Sokols.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The Fédération Internationale de Gymnastique (FIG), the French name for the International Gymnastics Federation, was founded in 1881 and remains the governing body of international gymnastics.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The organization began with three countries and was called the European Gymnastics Federation until 1921, when the first non-European countries joined, and it was reorganized into its modern form.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Gymnastics was included in the 1896 Summer Olympics, but female gymnasts were not allowed to participate in the Olympics until 1928.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The World Artistic Gymnastics Championships, held since 1903, were only open to men until 1934.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Since then, two branches of artistic gymnastics have developed: women's artistic gymnastics (WAG) and men's artistic gymnastics (MAG).
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Unlike men's and women's branches of many other sports, WAG and MAG differ significantly in technique and apparatuses used at major competitions.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] As a team event, women's gymnastics entered the Olympics in 1928 and the World Championships in 1950.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Individual women were recognized in the all-around as early as the 1934 World Championships.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The existing women's program—all-around and event finals on the vault, uneven bars, balance beam, and floor exercise—was introduced at the 1950 World Championships and at the 1952 Summer Olympics.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The earliest champions in women's gymnastics tended to be in their 20s, and most had studied ballet for years before entering the sport.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Larisa Latynina, the first great Soviet gymnast, won her first Olympic all-around medal at age 22 and her second at 26; she became world champion in 1958 while pregnant.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Věra Čáslavská of Czechoslovakia, who followed Latynina and became a two-time Olympic all-around champion, was 22 when she won her first Olympic gold medal.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The rules for the 1952 and 1956 Summer Olympics specified that gymnasts must turn 18 the year of the competition, with female gymnasts turning 16 or 17 only allowed to compete with a doctor's clearance.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] In the 1970s, the average age of Olympic gymnasts began to decrease.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] While it was not unheard of for teenagers to compete in the 1960s – Ludmilla Tourischeva was 16 at her first Olympics in 1968 – younger female gymnasts slowly became the norm as the sport's difficulty increased.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Smaller, lighter girls generally excelled in the more challenging acrobatic elements required by the redesigned Code of Points.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The 58th Congress of the FIG – held in July 1980, just before the Olympics – decided to raise the minimum age for senior international competition from 14 to 15.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] However, the change, which came into effect two years later, did not eliminate the problem.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] By the time of the 1992 Summer Olympics, elite gymnasts consisted almost exclusively of "pixies" – underweight young teenagers – and concerns were raised about athletes' welfare.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] In 1997, the FIG responded to this trend by raising the minimum age for international elite competition to 16.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] This, combined with changes in the Code of Points and evolving popular opinion in the sport, led to the return of older gymnasts.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] While there are still gymnasts who are successful as teenagers, it is common to see gymnasts competing and winning medals well into their 20s.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] At the 2004 Olympics, women captained both the second-place American team and the third-place Russians in their mid-20s; several other teams, including those from Australia, France, and Canada, included older gymnasts as well.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] At the 2008 Olympics, the silver medalist on vault, Oksana Chusovitina, was 33 years old.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] By the 2016 Olympics, the average age of female gymnasts was over 20, and it was almost 22 at the 2020 Olympics.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] At the 2024 Olympics the average age for the medal winning teams were USA: 22.2 years; Italy: 19.6 years; Brazil: 25.2 years.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Both male and female gymnasts are judged for execution, degree of difficulty, and overall presentation.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] In many competitions, especially high-level ones sanctioned by the FIG, gymnasts compete in "Olympic order", which has changed over time but has stayed consistent for at least a few decades.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The vault is both an event and the primary equipment used in that event.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Unlike most gymnastic events employing apparatuses, the vault is standard in men's and women's competitions, with little difference.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] A gymnast sprints down a runway, which is a maximum of 25 m (82 ft) in length, before leaping onto a springboard.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Harnessing the energy of the spring, the gymnast directs their body hands-first toward the vault.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Body position is maintained while "popping" (blocking using only a shoulder movement) the vaulting platform.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The gymnast then rotates their body to land standing on the far side of the vault.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] In advanced gymnastics, multiple twists and somersaults may be added before landing.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Successful vaults depend on the speed of the run, the length of the hurdle, the power the gymnast generates from the legs and shoulder girdle, kinesthetic awareness in the air, and the speed of rotation in the case of more challenging and complex vaults.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] In 2004, the traditional vaulting horse was replaced with a new apparatus, sometimes known as a tongue or table.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] It is more stable, wider, and longer than the older vaulting horse—about 1 m (3.3 ft) in length and width, giving gymnasts a larger blocking surface—and is, therefore, safer than the old vaulting horse.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] This new, safer apparatus led gymnasts to attempt more difficult vaults.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The floor event occurs on a carpeted 12 m × 12 m (39 ft × 39 ft) square consisting of rigid foam over a layer of plywood supported by springs or foam blocks.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] This provides a firm surface that will respond with force when compressed, allowing gymnasts to achieve extra height and a softer landing than possible on a regular floor.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Men perform without music for 60 to 70 seconds and must touch each floor corner at least once during their routine.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Their routines include tumbling passes demonstrating flexibility, strength, balance, and power.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] They must also show non-acrobatic skills, including circles, scales, and press handstands.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Women perform a 90-second choreographed routine to instrumental music.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Their routines include tumbling passes, jumps, dance elements, acrobatic skills, and turns.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Elite gymnasts may perform up to four tumbling passes.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] A typical pommel horse exercise involves both single-leg and double-leg work.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Single-leg skills are generally found in the form of "scissors".
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] In double leg work, the gymnast swings both legs in a circular motion (clockwise or counterclockwise, depending on preference).
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] To make the exercise more challenging, gymnasts will often include variations on typical circling skills by turning ("moores" and "spindles") or by straddling their legs ("flares").
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Routines end when the gymnast performs a dismount by swinging his body over the horse or landing after a handstand.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The still rings are suspended on wire cable from a point 5.8 m (19 ft) off the floor and adjusted in height so the gymnast has room to hang freely and swing.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Gymnasts must demonstrate balance, strength, power, and dynamic motion while preventing the rings themselves from swinging.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] At least one static strength move is required, but some gymnasts include two or three.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The parallel bars consist of two bars slightly further than shoulder-width apart and usually 1.75 m (5.7 ft) high.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Gymnasts execute a series of swings, balancing moves, and releases that require strength and coordination.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The horizontal bar (also known as the high bar) is a 2.4 cm (0.94 in) thick steel bar raised 2.5 m (8.2 ft) above the ground.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The gymnast performs 'giants' (360-degree revolutions around the bar), release skills, twists, and direction changes.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Using the momentum from giants, enough height can be achieved for spectacular dismounts, such as a triple-back somersault.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Leather grips are usually used to help maintain a hold on the bar.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The uneven bars (known as asymmetric bars in the United Kingdom) were adapted by the Czechoslovak Sokol from the men's parallel bars sometime before World War I and were shown in international exhibition for the first time at the 1928 Summer Olympics in Amsterdam.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] They consist of two horizontal bars set at different heights.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Gymnasts perform swings, pirouettes, transition moves between the bars, and releases.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Higher-level gymnasts usually wear leather grips to ensure a firm hold on the bars while protecting their hands from painful blisters and tears (known as rips).
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Gymnasts sometimes wet their grips with water from a spray bottle and may apply chalk to prevent the grips from slipping.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Chalk may also be applied to the hands and bar if grips are not worn.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The balance beam existed as early as the 1880s in the form of a "low beam" close to the floor.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] By the 1920s, the beam was raised much higher due to Swedish influence on the sport.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Gymnasts perform routines ranging from 70 to 90 seconds long, consisting of leaps, acrobatic skills, turns, and dance elements on a padded spring beam.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Apparatus norms set by the FIG specify that the beam must be 125 cm (4 ft) high, 500 cm (16 ft) long, and 10 cm (3.9 in) wide.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The event requires balance, flexibility, and strength.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] In Olympic and World Championship competitions, meets are divided into several sessions on different days: qualifications, team finals, all-around finals, and event finals.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] During the *qualification* round (abbreviated TQ), gymnasts compete with their national squad in all four (WAG) or six (MAG) events.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The scores from this session are not used to award medals but rather to determine which teams advance to the team finals and which individual gymnasts advance to the all-around and event finals.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] For the 2020 Olympics, teams will consist of four gymnasts, with up to two additional gymnasts per country allowed to compete as individuals.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The format of team qualifications is 4–4–3, meaning that all four gymnasts compete in each event, but only the top three scores count.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Individual gymnasts may qualify for the all-around and event finals, but their scores do not count toward the team's total.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] In the *team finals* (abbreviated TF), gymnasts compete with their national squad on all four or six events.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The scores from the session determine the medalists in the team competition.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The format is 4–3–3, meaning that of the four gymnasts on the team, three compete in each event, and all three scores count.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] In the *all-around* finals (abbreviated AA), gymnasts compete individually in all four or six events; their totals determine the all-around medals.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Only two gymnasts per country may advance to the all-around finals from the qualification round.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] In the *event finals* (abbreviated EF) or *apparatus finals*, the top eight gymnasts in each event (as determined by scores in the qualification round) compete for medals.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Only two gymnasts per country may advance to each event final.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Competitions other than the Olympics and World Championships may use different formats.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] For instance, the 2007 Pan American Games had only one team competition day with a 6–5–4 format, and three athletes per country were allowed to advance to the all-around.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The team event is not contested in other meets, such as on the World Cup circuit.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Since 1989, competitions have used the "new life" rule, under which scores from one session do not carry over to the next.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] In other words, a gymnast's performance in team finals does not affect their scores in the all-around finals or event finals, and marks from the team qualifying round do not count toward the team finals.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Before this rule was introduced, the scores from the team competition carried over into the all-around and event finals.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Until 1997, the team competition consisted of two sessions, with every gymnast performing standardized *compulsory routines* in the preliminaries and individualized *optional routines* on the second day.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Team medals were determined based on the combined scores of both days, as were the qualifiers to the all-around and event finals.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] However, the all-around and event finals did not include compulsory routines.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] In meets where team titles were not contested, such as the American Cup, there were two days of all-around competition: one for compulsories and another for optionals.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] While each gymnast and their coach developed optional routines in accordance with the Code of Points and the gymnast's strengths, compulsory routines were created and choreographed by the FIG Technical Committee.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The dance and tumbling skills were generally less demanding than those in optional routines, but perfect technique, form, and execution were heavily emphasized.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Scoring was exacting, with judges taking deductions for even slight deviations from the required choreography.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] For this reason, many gymnasts and coaches considered compulsories more challenging than optionals.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Compulsory exercises were eliminated at the end of 1996.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The move was highly controversial, with many successful gymnastics federations—including the United States, Russia, and China—arguing that the compulsory exercises helped maintain a high standard of form, technique, and execution among gymnasts.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Opponents of compulsory exercises believed that they harmed emerging gymnastics programs.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Some members of the gymnastics community still argue that compulsories should be reinstated, and many gymnastics federations have maintained compulsories in their national programs.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Often, gymnasts competing at the lower levels of the sport—for instance, Levels 2–5 in USA Gymnastics, Grade 2 in South Africa, and Levels 3–6 in Australia—only perform compulsory routines.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Artistic gymnasts compete only with other gymnasts at their level.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Each athlete starts at the lowest level and advances to higher levels by learning more complex skills and achieving qualifying scores at competitions.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] In the United States, whose program is governed by USA Gymnastics, levels range from 1 to 10, followed by elite.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Levels 1 to 2 are usually considered recreational or beginner; 3 to 6 intermediate; and 7 to elite advanced.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Competitions begin at Level 3 or, in some gyms, Level 2.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] A gymnast must be able to perform specific skills in each event to advance to the next level.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Once a gymnast has competed in a sectional meet at a given level, they may not drop back to a lower level in the same competitive season.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Gymnasts in Levels 1–2 perform basic skills such as handstands and cartwheels.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Levels 3–5 consist of compulsory routines; 6 is an in-between level with strict requirements but some leeway for gymnasts to show their creativity; and Levels 7–10 consist of optional routines.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Only elite gymnasts compete in accordance with the FIG's Code of Points; lower levels have a modified code.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The elite program is divided into two categories: junior for gymnasts younger than 16, and senior for gymnasts 16 and older.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] (Gymnasts are allowed to compete at the senior level at the beginning of the calendar year in which they will turn 16.) Olympic teams are chosen from the senior elite program.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The British Gymnastics level system goes from 5 (lowest) to 2, and there are separate tracks for elite- and club-level competition.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] There are several competitive streams in Canadian gymnastics: recreational, developmental, pre-competitive, provincial, national, and high-performance.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Provincial levels range from 5 (lowest) to 1; national levels are pre-novice, novice, open, and high performance; and high-performance levels are novice, junior, and senior.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] In Germany, there are different competitive systems for recreational and high-performance gymnasts.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Recreational gymnasts have a system of compulsory exercises from 1 to 9 and optional exercises from 4 to 1, with modified Code of Points requirements.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] For high-performance and junior athletes, there are compulsory and optional requirements defined by age, from ages 6 to 18.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The FIG imposes a minimum age requirement on gymnasts competing in certain international meets, but it does not impose a maximum age limit.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The term *senior* refers to world-class or elite gymnasts who are age-eligible under FIG rules: Female gymnasts must be at least 16 or turning 16 within the calendar year, and the minimum age for men is 18.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The term *junior* refers to any gymnast who competes at a world-class or elite level but is too young to be classified as a senior.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Juniors are judged under the same Code of Points as seniors and often exhibit the same difficulty level in their routines.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Still, they cannot compete at the Olympics, World Championships, or World Cups.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Many meets, such as the European Championships, have separate divisions for juniors.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] But some competitions, such as the Goodwill Games, the Pan American Games, the Pacific Rim Championships, and the All-Africa Games, permit seniors and juniors to compete together.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The age requirement is contentious and is frequently debated by coaches, gymnasts, and other members of the gymnastics community.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Those in favor of the age limits argue that they promote the participation of older athletes and spare younger gymnasts from the stress of competition and high-level training.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Opponents point out that junior gymnasts are scored under the same Code of Points as the seniors (with some restrictions) and train mainly with the same skills.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] They also argue that younger gymnasts need the experience of competing in major events to improve as athletes.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Since stricter age requirements were adopted in the early 1980s, there have been several well-documented and many more suspected cases of juniors with falsified documents competing as seniors.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Scoring at the international level is regulated by the Code of Points.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Under the system established in 2006, two panels judge each routine, evaluating different aspects of the performance.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The *D score* covers skill requirements, difficulty value, and connection value (for skills performed back to back with no pause in between); the *E score* covers execution and artistry; the two are added together to produce final scores.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The maximum E score is 10, but there is no cap on the D score.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Theoretically, this means scores could be infinite.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] However, average marks for routines in major competitions have generally been in the low to mid-teens.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] This system, with its open-ended difficulty score, is very different from the one used for most of the sport's history.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Before 2006, the highest possible score was a "perfect 10".
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Every routine was assigned a start value (SV) based on difficulty.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] A routine that included all required elements received a base SV—9.4 in 1996, 9.0 in 1997, 8.8 in 2001—and gymnasts could increase their SV to a maximum of 10 by performing more challenging skills and combinations.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Then, to score a gymnast's routine, judges deducted from the SV for errors in execution.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Some gymnasts and coaches—including Olympic gold medalists Lilia Podkopayeva, Svetlana Boginskaya, Shannon Miller, and Vitaly Scherbo, and Romanian team coach Nicolae Forminte — publicly opposed the new Code of Points when it was first announced.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] In addition, a 2006 report from the FIG Athletes' Commission cited significant concerns about scoring, judging, and other subjects.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Aspects of the code were revised in 2007, but there are no plans to return to the "perfect 10" format.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Most countries hold a major competition (National Championships, or "Nationals") every year that determines the best-performing all-around gymnasts and event specialists.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Based on their scores at Nationals, gymnasts may qualify for their country's national team or be selected for international meets.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Before the breakup of the Soviet Union in 1991, Soviet gymnasts dominated both men's and women's gymnastics, starting with the introduction of the full women's program into the Olympics and the overall increased standardization of the Olympic gymnastics competition format, which happened in 1952.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The Soviet Union had many male stars, such as Olympic all-around champions Viktor Chukarin and Vitaly Scherbo, and female stars, such as Olympic all-around champions Larisa Latynina and Svetlana Boginskaya.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] From 1952 to 1992 inclusive, the Soviet women's squad won almost every team title in World Championship and Olympic competition, with only four exceptions: the 1984 Olympics, which the country boycotted, and the 1966, 1979, and 1987 World Championships.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Most of the top Soviet gymnasts were from the Russian SFSR, the Ukrainian SSR, and the Byelorussian SSR, with the most famous, Olga Korbut, hailing from the latter.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The artistry and grace of Korbut, along with that of Nadia Comăneci of Romania, brought unprecedented global popularity to the sport in the early to mid-1970s.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Following the breakup of the Soviet Union, its gymnasts performed together for the last time at the 1992 Summer Olympics as the Unified Team, winning both the men's and women's team competitions.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Russia has continued the Soviet tradition, medaling at every World and Olympic competition in both MAG and WAG disciplines, except at the 2008 Olympics.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Ukraine maintained a strong team for more than a decade—Ukrainian Lilia Podkopayeva was the all-around champion at the 1996 Olympics—but it has declined in recent years.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Belarus has maintained a strong men's team.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Other former republics have been less successful.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The Romanian team first achieved wide-scale success at the 1976 Summer Olympics with the performance of Nadia Comăneci, who was the first gymnast to score a perfect 10 in Olympic competition.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] After that, using the centralized training system pioneered by Béla Károlyi, they remained a dominant force in women's team and individual events for nearly four decades.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Romania was one of only two teams ever to defeat the Soviets in head-to-head World or Olympic competition, winning at the 1979 and 1987 World Championships.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] (The other was the Czechoslovak women's team at the 1966 World Championships.) The Romanian women also won team medals at every Olympics from 1976 to 2012 inclusive, including gold medals in 1984, 2000, and 2004.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] At the 16 World Championships from 1978 to 2007 inclusive, they failed to medal only twice (in 1981 and 2006) and won the team title seven times, including five victories in a row (1994–2001).
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The decline of Romanian gymnastics began after the 2004 Summer Olympics.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] At the 2006 World Championships, they failed to medal in the team competition, and only Sandra Izbașa won any individual medals.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] They won bronze medals at the 2007 World Championships, 2008 Summer Olympics, and 2012 Summer Olympics but failed to medal at the 2010, 2011, or 2014 World Championships.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Things took a drastic turn at the 2015 World Championships, where Romania did not even qualify for the team final.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] In 2016, it failed to qualify a full team to the 2016 Summer Olympics, placing seventh at the 2016 Gymnastics Olympic Test Event.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] It earned one Olympic spot, which was filled by 3-time Olympic champion Cătălina Ponor.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] At the 2018 World Championships, Romania placed 13th in qualifications and did not make the team final.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] At the 2019 World Championships, it finished 22nd out of 24 teams—beating only the Czech Republic and Egypt—and again failed to qualify a team to the 2020 Summer Olympics, with only Maria Holbură earning an individual spot.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] After the Olympics were postponed due to the COVID-19 pandemic, a second Romanian gymnast, Larisa Iordache, earned an individual spot through the 2021 European Championships.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] While less successful than the women's program, the Romanian men's program has produced individual medalists such as Marian Drăgulescu and Marius Urzică at World and Olympic competitions.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The defection of Eastern Bloc coaches in the early 1980s, such as the Romanian husband and wife team of Béla and Márta Károlyi, were credited with transforming the coaching of gymnastics in the U.S. and bringing major international success.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] At the 1984 Olympics, which the Soviet bloc boycotted, the American men won the gold with a team composed of Bart Conner, Tim Daggett, Mitch Gaylord, Jim Hartung, Scott Johnson, and Peter Vidmar.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The women's team—composed of Pam Bileck, Michelle Dusserre, Kathy Johnson, Julianne McNamara, Mary Lou Retton, and Tracee Talavera—won a silver medal, and Retton became the first American Olympic all-around champion.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] In 1991, Kim Zmeskal became the first American all-around winner at the World Championships.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] At the 1992 Olympics, the American women won their first team medal (bronze) at a fully attended Games, as well as their highest all-around ranking, a silver medal for Shannon Miller.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] In men's gymnastics, Trent Dimas won the horizontal bar final.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The U.S. women's team has become increasingly successful in the modern era, with the 1996 Olympic team victory of the Magnificent Seven, the 2003 Worlds team victory, and multiple medals in both WAG and MAG at the 2004 Olympics.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] At the 2012 Olympics and 2016 Olympics, the U.S. women won the team gold.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] At the 2005 World Championships, American women won the gold and silver in the all-around and in every event final except vault (where Alicia Sacramone placed third).
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] They continue to be one of the most dominant forces in the sport.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The men's team made the medal podium at the 2004, 2008, and 2024 Olympics, as well as the 2003 and 2011 World Championships.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Paul Hamm, the most successful U.S. male gymnast, became the first American man to win a World all-around title in 2003.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] He followed this up by winning the all-around at the 2004 Olympics.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Jonathan Horton won a silver medal on the horizontal bar at the 2008 Olympics and a bronze in the all-around at the 2010 World Championships, and Danell Leyva won the all-around bronze medal at the 2012 Olympics and two silver medals (parallel bars and horizontal bar) at the 2016 Olympics.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] China has had successful men's and women's programs over the past 25 years.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The Chinese men won team gold at the 2000, 2008, and 2012 Olympics and every World Championship team title from 1994 to 2014 (except 2001, when they placed fifth).
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] They have produced individual gymnasts like Olympic all-around champions Li Xiaoshuang (1996) and Yang Wei (2008).
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The Chinese women's team won gold at the 2006 World Championships and 2008 Olympics, and has produced individual gymnasts like Mo Huilan, Kui Yuanyuan, Yang Bo, Cheng Fei, Sui Lu, Huang Huidan, Yao Jinnan, and Fan Yilin.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Chinese women who have won individual Olympic gold medals are Ma Yanhong, Lu Li, Liu Xuan, He Kexin, Deng Linlin, and Guan Chenchen.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Though for many years considered a two-event team (uneven bars and balance beam), China has developed successful all-arounders like Olympic bronze medalists Liu Xuan (2000), Zhang Nan (2004), and Yang Yilin (2008).
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Like the Soviet Union, they have been accused of grueling and sometimes cruel training methods, as well as age falsification.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The Japanese men's team was dominant during the 1960s and 1970s, winning every Olympic team title from 1960 through 1976 thanks to individual gymnasts such as Olympic all-around champions Sawao Katō and Yukio Endō.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Several innovations pioneered by Japanese gymnasts during this era have remained in the sport, including the Tsukahara vault.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] More recently, Japanese men have re-emerged as top contenders since winning a team gold at the 2004 Olympics.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Six-time World champion and two-time Olympic all-around gold medalist Kōhei Uchimura is widely considered to be the best all-around gymnast ever, and Hiroyuki Tomita won 10 World and Olympic medals from 2003 to 2008.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Tsurumi won a bronze medal in the all-around and silver on bars at the 2009 World Championships, and Murakami won gold on floor in 2017, the first Japanese woman to win a World gold medal since Tanaka-Ikeda.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The German Democratic Republic, or East Germany, had a very successful gymnastics program before the reunification of Germany.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Its MAG and WAG teams frequently won silver or bronze medals at the World Championships and Olympics, led by male gymnasts such as Andreas Wecker and Roland Brückner, and female gymnasts such as Maxi Gnauck, Karin Janz, and Erika Zuchold.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The Federal Republic of Germany, or West Germany, had international stars like Eberhard Gienger, Willi Jaschek, and Helmut Bantz.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Since its reunification, Germany has produced some medal-winning gymnasts, including Fabian Hambüchen, Philipp Boy, and Marcel Nguyen among the men and Pauline Schäfer, Elizabeth Seitz, Sophie Scheder, and Tabea Alt among the women.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The former Soviet/Uzbek gymnast Oksana Chusovitina also competed for Germany from 2006 to 2012, winning two World medals and an Olympic silver on vault.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The Czechoslovak women's team was the main threat to the dominance of the Soviet women's team for decades.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] They won team medals at every World Championships and Olympics from 1934 to 1970, with the exceptions of the 1950 Worlds and 1956 Olympics.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The Czechoslovakia men's success at the World Championships was the greatest of any country before World War II: They were first in the medal table more than any other nation and won the most team titles during the pre-WWII period.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Together, Czechoslovakia and its precursor, the Austro-Hungarian constituent Bohemia, produced four men's World all-around champions: Josef Čada in 1907, Ferdinand Steiner in 1911, František Pecháček in 1922, and Jan Gajdoš in 1938.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Their most decorated athlete was Ladislav Vácha, who won 10 individual World and Olympic medals.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Led by individuals such as 10-time Olympic medalist (with five golds) Ágnes Keleti, the Hungarian women's team medaled at the first four Olympics that included women's artistic gymnastics competitions (1936–1956), as well as at the 1954 World Championships.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] After a long decline, World and Olympic vault champion Henrietta Ónodi put them back on the map in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The Hungarian men never had the same level of success as the women.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] However, Zoltán Magyar dominated the pommel horse in the 1970s, winning eight of a possible nine European, World, and Olympic titles from 1973 to 1980.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Szilveszter Csollány, a World and Olympic champion on rings, also won medals at major competitions for a decade starting in the early 1990s.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] In more recent years, Krisztián Berki has won World and Olympic titles on the pommel horse.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Several other nations have been strong competitors in WAG and MAG.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The rise of various countries' programs in recent years is partly due to the large exodus of coaching talent from the USSR and other former Eastern Bloc countries.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] In the past two decades, Australia, Brazil, Great Britain, Canada, France, Italy, the Netherlands, and South Korea have produced World and Olympic medalists and have started winning team medals at continental, World and Olympic competitions.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Individual gymnasts from Croatia, Greece, North Korea, Slovenia, Spain, and Ireland have also been successful in major competitions.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Gymnastics sits on many lists of the world's most dangerous sports.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Artistic gymnastics carries an inherently high risk of spinal and other injuries, and in extremely rare cases, gymnasts have sustained fatal injuries.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Julissa Gomez, an American gymnast, died in 1991 after breaking her neck while vaulting three years earlier.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Several other gymnasts have been paralyzed from accidents in training or competition, including Elena Mukhina of the Soviet Union and Sang Lan of China.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The pressure of the sport can make it even more dangerous to athletes.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Coaches frequently put pressure on their gymnasts to perform well, which can hinder their visual attention, memory, and ability to focus on the task at hand, in turn negatively affecting performance.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Moreover, this pressure often leads to extreme perfectionism in gymnasts, which is correlated with higher rates of anxiety disorders, including general anxiety disorder (GAD) and obsessive compulsive disorder (OCD).
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] During the Tokyo 2020 Olympics, gymnast Simone Biles took a step back from competition to assess her mental health and ensure she was not putting herself at a greater risk of physical injury.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Other athletes have expressed their support and called for a greater emphasis on mental health in gymnastics.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Eating disorders are also common, especially in women's gymnastics, in which gymnasts are motivated and sometimes pushed by coaches to maintain a below-normal body weight.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The problem gained public attention in the 1990s after the death of Christy Henrich, a U.S. national team member who suffered from anorexia and bulimia.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Abusive coaching and training practices in gymnastics gained widespread attention after Joan Ryan's book *Little Girls in Pretty Boxes* was published in 1995.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] USA Gymnastics began investigating several coaches in their program for abuse.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] In the late 2010s, many individual gymnasts—including former elite competitors from Australia, Britain, and the United States—began to speak out about the abuse they had experienced.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] This followed several years of allegations of sexual abuse by gymnastics coaches and other authority figures, including the former U.S. team doctor Larry Nassar.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] In April 2020, Maggie Haney, former coach of Olympian Laurie Hernandez, was suspended for eight years following her allegations of verbal and emotional abuse toward her gymnasts.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] During the 1996 Olympics, Kerri Strug injured her foot after her first vault.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] However, her vault was standing between Team USA and a gold medal.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Strug performed her second vault, landing on one foot, and was carried off by her coach, crying in pain.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Strug's teammate, Dominique Moceanu also opened up about the abuse she experienced.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] She said that she competed in the Olympics with a tibial stress fracture.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Additionally, she fell on her head during her beam routine and discussed how none of these injuries were properly treated.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] After being the coordinators for Team USA for nearly three decades in 2016, Bela and Marta Karolyi retired.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] After allegations that gymnasts were experiencing sexual abuse while training at the Karolyi ranch, it was officially closed in 2018.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] Upon investigations of those working closely with Larry Nassar, John Geddert, head coach of the 2012 Women's Olympic Team, was suspended by USA Gymnastics for sexual assault, physical abuse, and human trafficking, and committed suicide shortly after being charged in February 2021.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] The Federal Bureau of Investigation had heard allegations from gymnasts regarding their sexual abuse as early as 2015 but did not address them until years later when Nassar was sentenced to prison in 2017.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] At the time of Nassar's court hearing, more than 160 women had spoken up about the abuse they endured.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/artistic-gymnastics] In a Senate hearing from September 2021, the victims and their representatives claimed that Nassar had abused 120 more women from the time the FBI knew about his allegations until the time they took action against him.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The **Associated Press** (**AP**) is an American not-for-profit news agency headquartered in New York City.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Founded in 1846, it operates as a cooperative, unincorporated association, and produces news reports that are distributed to its members, major U.S. daily newspapers and radio and television broadcasters.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Since the Pulitzer Prize was established in 1917, the AP has earned 60 of them, including 36 for photography.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP distributes its widely used *AP Stylebook*, its AP polls tracking NCAA sports, and its election polls and results during U.S. elections.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] It sponsors the National Football League's annual awards.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] By 2016, news collected by the AP was published and republished by more than 1,300 newspapers and broadcasters.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP operates 235 news bureaus in 94 countries, and publishes in English, Spanish, and Arabic.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] It also operates the AP Radio Network, which provides twice hourly newscasts and daily sportscasts for broadcast and satellite radio and television stations.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Many newspapers and broadcasters outside the United States are AP subscribers, paying a fee to use AP material without being contributing members of the cooperative.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] As part of their cooperative agreement with the AP, most member news organizations grant automatic permission for the AP to distribute their local news reports.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] As of 2025, the AP attracts more than 128 million monthly website visits, making it one of the top 10 news websites in the U.S.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The Associated Press was formed in May 1846 by five daily newspapers in New York City to share the cost of transmitting news of the Mexican–American War.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The venture was organized by Moses Yale Beach (1800–68), second publisher of *The Sun*, joined by the *New York Herald*, the *New York Courier and Enquirer*, *The Journal of Commerce*, and the *New York Evening Express*.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Some historians believe that the *New-York Tribune* joined at this time; documents show it was a member in 1849.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] *The New York Times* became a member in September 1851.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Initially known as the New York Associated Press (NYAP), the organization faced competition from the Western Associated Press (1862), which criticized its monopolistic news gathering and price setting practices.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] An investigation completed in 1892 by Victor Lawson, editor and publisher of the *Chicago Daily News*, revealed that several principals of the NYAP entered into a secret agreement with United Press, a rival organization, to share NYAP news and the profits of reselling it.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The findings led to the dissolving of the NYAP.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] That December, the Western Associated Press was incorporated in Illinois as the Associated Press.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] A 1900 Illinois Supreme Court decision (*Inter Ocean Publishing Co. v.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Associated Press*) holding that the AP was a public utility and operating in restraint of trade resulted in the AP's move from Chicago to New York City, where corporation laws were more favorable to cooperatives.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In 1935, the AP launched the Wirephoto network, which allowed transmission of news photographs over leased private telephone lines on the day they were taken.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] This gave the AP a major advantage over other news media outlets.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] While the first network was only between New York, Chicago, and San Francisco, eventually the AP had its network across the whole United States.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In 1945, the Supreme Court of the United States held in *Associated Press v.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] United States* that the AP had been violating the Sherman Antitrust Act by prohibiting member newspapers from selling or providing news to nonmember organizations as well as making it very difficult for nonmember newspapers to join the AP.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP entered the broadcast field in 1941 when it began distributing news to radio stations; it created its own radio network in 1974.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In 1994, it established APTV, a global video newsgathering agency.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] APTV merged with Worldwide Television News in 1998 to form APTN, which provides video to international broadcasters and websites.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In 2004, the AP moved its headquarters from its long-time home at 50 Rockefeller Plaza to 450 West 33rd Street in Manhattan.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In 2019, AP had more than 240 bureaus globally.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Its mission has not changed since its founding, but digital technology has made the distribution of the AP news report an interactive endeavor between the AP and its hundreds of U.S. newspaper members, as well as broadcasters, international subscribers, and online customers.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP began diversifying its news gathering capabilities.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] By 2007, the AP was generating only about 30% of its revenue from United States newspapers, and by 2024, this had declined to 10%.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] 37% came from the global broadcast customers, 15% from online ventures and 18% came from international newspapers and from photography.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In March 2024, Gannett, the largest U.S. newspaper publisher as measured by total daily circulation, announced that effective March 25, 2024, it would no longer use content from the AP.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] A spokesperson for AP said that they were "shocked and disappointed" by this development.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Newspaper chain McClatchy announced that it would also stop using some AP services.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Gannett and McClatchy will both continue to use AP's election results data.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP's multi-topic structure has resulted in web portals such as Yahoo! and MSN posting its articles, often relying on the AP as their first source for news coverage of breaking news items.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] This and the constant updating evolving stories require has had a major impact on the AP's public image and role, giving new credence to the AP's ongoing mission of having staff for covering every area of news fully and promptly.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In 2007, Google announced that it was paying to receive AP content, to be displayed in Google News, interrupted from late 2009 to mid-2010 due to a licensing dispute.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] A 2017 study by NewsWhip revealed that AP content was more engaged with on Facebook than content from any individual English-language publisher.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP is governed by an elected board of directors.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Since 2022, the board's chairperson is Gracia C.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Martore, former president and CEO of Tegna, Inc.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] AP reports from countries where press freedom is restricted, sometimes under adverse circumstances, and operates out of more than 100 regional offices.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In 2025, restrictions preventing AP reporting in the U.S. were imposed by the second Trump administration.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In February 2025, two AP reporters were barred from covering several events at the White House, because of the AP refusal to refer to the Gulf of Mexico as the "Gulf of America", as directed by the White House.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The restrictions against AP were extended to other reporting opportunities such as in Air Force One.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] On February 21, 2025, the AP sued the Trump administration in *Associated Press v.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Budowich* for blocking their attendance.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] On February 24, 2025, a federal judge declined to issue an immediate order compelling the White House to reinstate access to presidential events to AP, although he encouraged the White House to do so.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] On April 8, 2025, Judge Trevor McFadden ruled that the White House must lift the access restrictions they placed on the AP while the *AP v.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] On June 6, 2025, the United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit imposed a stay upon the lower court's order, allowing the White House to resume barring access to some media events.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP is one of two organizations that collect and verify election results in every city and county across the United States, including races for the U.S. president, the Senate and House of Representatives, and governors as well as other statewide offices.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Known for accuracy, the organization has collected and published presidential election data since 1848.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Major news outlets rely on the polling data and results provided by the Associated Press before declaring a winner in major political races, particularly the presidential election.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In declaring the winners, the AP has historically relied on a robust network of local reporters with first-hand knowledge of assigned territories who also have long-standing relationships with county clerks as well as other local officials.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Moreover, the AP monitors and gathers data from county websites and electronic feeds provided by states.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The research team further verifies the results by considering demographics, number of absentee ballots, and other political issues that may have an effect on the final results.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In 2018, the AP introduced a new system called AP VoteCast, which was developed together with NORC at the University of Chicago in order to further improve the reliability of its data and overcome biases of its legacy exit poll.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP conducts polls for numerous college sports in the United States.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP college football rankings were created in 1936, and began including the top 25 teams in 1989.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Since 1969, the final poll of each season has been released after all bowl games have been played.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP released its all-time Top 25 in 2016.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] As of 2017, 22 different programs had finished in the number one spot of the poll since its inception.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In the pre-bowl game determination era, the AP poll was often used as the distinction for a national champion in football.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP college basketball poll has been used as a guide for which teams deserve national attention.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP first began its poll of college basketball teams in 1949, and has since conducted over 1,100 polls.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The college basketball poll started with 20 teams and was reduced to 10 during the 1960–61 college basketball season.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] It returned to 20 teams in 1968–69 and expanded to 25 beginning in 1989–90.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The final poll for each season is released prior to the conclusion of the NCAA tournament, so all data includes regular season games only.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In 2017, The AP released a list of the Top 100 teams of all time.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The poll counted poll appearances (one point) and No.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] 1 rankings (two points) to rank each team.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP began its Major League Baseball Manager of the Year Award in 1959, for a manager in each league.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] From 1984 to 2000, the award was given to one manager in all of MLB.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The winners were chosen by a national panel of AP baseball writers and radio men.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Every year, the AP releases the names of the winners of its AP College Basketball Player of the Year and AP College Basketball Coach of the Year awards.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] It also honors a group of All-American players.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In 1994, London-based Associated Press Television (APTV) was founded to provide agency news material to television broadcasters.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In 1998, the AP purchased Worldwide Television News (WTN) from the ABC News division of The Walt Disney Company, Nine Network Australia and ITN London.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP publishes 70,000 videos and 6,000 hours of live video per year, as of 2016.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The agency also provides seven simultaneous live video channels, AP Direct for broadcasters, and six live channels on AP Live Choice for broadcasters and digital publishers.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP was the first news agency to launch a live video news service in 2003.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The first publicly available edition of the book was published in 1953.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The first modern edition was published in August 1977 by Lorenz Press.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Afterwards, various paperback editions were published by different publishers, including, among others, Turtleback Books, Penguin's Laurel Press, Pearson's Addison-Wesley, and Hachette's Perseus Books and Basic Books.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Recent editions are released in several formats, including paperback and flat-lying spiral-bound editions, as well as a digital e-book edition and an online subscription version.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Additionally, the *AP Stylebook* also provides English grammar recommendations through social media, including Twitter, Facebook, Pinterest, and Instagram.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] From 1977 to 2005, more than two million copies of the *AP Stylebook* were sold worldwide, with that number climbing to 2.5 million by 2011.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Writers in broadcasting, news, magazine publishing, marketing departments, and public relations firms traditionally adopt and apply AP grammar and punctuation styles.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP collaborated with Nazi Germany and gave it access to its photographic archives for its antisemitic Nazi propaganda.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] AP also cooperated with the Nazi regime through censorship.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In 2017, the German historian Norman Domeier of the University of Vienna brought to wider attention the deal between the AP and the Nazi government related to the interchange of press photos during the period in which the United States was at war with Nazi Germany.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] This relationship involved the Bureau Laux, run by the Waffen-SS photographer Helmut Laux.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The mechanism for this interchange involved a courier flying to Lisbon and back each day transporting photos from and for Nazi Germany's wartime enemy, the United States, via diplomatic pouch.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The transactions were initially conducted at the AP bureau under Luiz Lupi in Lisbon, and from 1944, when the exchange via Lisbon took too long, also at the AP bureau in Stockholm under Eddie Shanke.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Here, as a cover, the Swedish agency, Pressens Bild, was involved as an intermediary.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] An estimated 40,000 photos were exchanged between the enemies in this way.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP was kicked out of Nazi Germany when the United States entered World War II in December 1941.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Israeli journalist Matti Friedman accused the AP of killing a story he wrote about the "war of words", "between Israel and its critics in human rights organizations", in the aftermath of the 2008–2009 Gaza war.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] On September 29, 2000, the first day of the Second Intifada, the AP published a photograph of a badly-bloodied young man behind whom a police officer could be seen with a baton raised in a menacing fashion; a gas station with Hebrew lettering could also be seen in the background.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP labelled it with the caption "An Israeli policeman and a Palestinian on the Temple Mount", and the picture and caption were subsequently published in several major American newspapers, including the *New York Times*.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In reality, the injured man in the photograph was a Jewish yeshiva student from Chicago named Tuvia Grossman, and the police officer, a Druze named Gidon Tzefadi, was protecting Grossman from a Palestinian mob who had clubbed, stoned, and stabbed Grossman.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] There are also no gas stations with Hebrew lettering on the Temple Mount.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The episode is often cited by those who accuse the media of having an anti-Israel bias, and was the impetus for the founding of the pro-Israel group HonestReporting.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] After a letter from Grossman's father noted the error, the AP, the *New York Times*, and other papers published corrections; despite these corrections, the photograph continues to be used by critics of Israel as a symbol of Israeli aggression and violence.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] During the 2021 Israel–Palestine crisis, the Israeli army destroyed the al-Jalaa Highrise, a building housing the AP's Gaza offices and Al Jazeera offices.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Israel stated that the building housed Hamas military intelligence and had given advanced warning of the strike, and no civilians were harmed.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] AP CEO Gary Pruitt released a statement on May 16, stating that he "had no indication Hamas was in the building" and called on the Israeli government to provide the evidence.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] On May 17, US secretary of state Antony Blinken said he had not seen any evidence that Hamas operated from the building housing the AP and Al Jazeera, but it is the job of others to handle intelligence matters.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Israel reportedly shared intelligence with American officials and U.S. president Joe Biden showing Hamas offices inside the building.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Reporters Without Borders asked the International Criminal Court to investigate the bombing as a possible war crime.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] On June 8, the Israeli ambassador to the US, Gilad Erdan, met with AP CEO Gary Pruitt and vice president for foreign news, Ian Phillips, to discuss the operation.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In coordination with the IDF, Erdan said the site was used by Hamas intelligence officials to develop and carry out electronic warfare operations, and that IDF did not suspect the AP was aware of the alleged covert Hamas presence.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] After the meeting the AP stated "We have yet to receive evidence to support these claims".
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In May 2024, Israeli officials seized equipment broadcasting a live stream of Northern Gaza from the town of Sderot as part of a ban on Al Jazeera Media in Israel which had received footage from the broadcast.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The move was condemned by multiple journalism organizations, Israeli opposition politicians, and US government officials.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In 1994, Tina Susman was on her fourth trip to Somalia, reporting for the AP.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] She was reporting on U.S. peacekeeping troops leaving the country.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Somali rebels outnumbered her bodyguards in Mogadishu, dragged her from her car in broad daylight, and held her for 20 days.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] She told *The Quill* that she believes being a woman was an advantage in her experience there.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP had requested news organizations including *The New York Times*, the *Chicago Tribune,* and *The Washington Post* to suppress the story to discourage the emboldening of the kidnappers.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In September 2002, Washington, D.C. bureau reporter Christopher Newton, an AP reporter since 1994, was fired after he was accused of fabricating sources since 2000, including at least 40 people and organizations.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Prior to his firing, Newton had been focused on writing about federal law enforcement while based at the Justice Department.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Some of the nonexistent agencies quoted in his stories included "Education Alliance", the "Institute for Crime and Punishment in Chicago", "Voice for the Disabled", and "People for Civil Rights".
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In 2007, an FBI agent working in Seattle impersonated an AP journalist and infected the computer of a 15-year-old suspect with malicious surveillance software.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The incident sparked a strongly worded statement from the AP demanding that the bureau never impersonate a member of the news media again.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In September 2016, the incident resulted in a report by the Justice Department, which the AP said "effectively condone[d] the FBI's impersonation".
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In December 2017, following a US court appearance, a judge ruled in favor of the AP in a lawsuit against the FBI for fraudulently impersonating a member of the news media in conjunction with the 2007 case.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In June 2008, the AP sent numerous DMCA take-down demands and threatened legal action against several blogs.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP contended that the internet blogs were violating the AP's copyright by linking to AP material and using headlines and short summaries in those links.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Many bloggers and experts noted that the use of the AP news fell squarely under commonly accepted internet practices and within fair-use standards.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Others noted and demonstrated that the AP routinely takes similar excerpts from other sources, often without attribution or licenses.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP responded that it was defining standards regarding citations of AP news.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In March 2009, the AP counter-sued artist Shepard Fairey over his famous image of Barack Obama, saying the uncredited, uncompensated use of an AP photo violated copyright laws and signaled a threat to journalism.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Fairey had sued the AP the previous month over his artwork, titled "Obama Hope" and "Obama Progress", arguing that he did not violate copyright law because he dramatically changed the image.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The artwork, based on an April 2006 picture taken for the AP by Mannie Garcia, was a popular image during the 2008 presidential election and now hangs in the National Portrait Gallery in Washington, D.C.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] According to the AP's lawsuit filed in federal court in Manhattan, Fairey knowingly "misappropriated The AP's rights in that image".
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The suit asked the court to award the AP profits made off the image and damages.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Fairey said he looked forward to "upholding the free expression rights at stake here" and disproving the AP's accusations.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In January 2011, the suit was settled with neither side declaring their position to be wrong but agreeing to share reproduction rights and profits from Fairey's work.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In January 2008, the AP sued competitor All Headline News (AHN) claiming that AHN allegedly infringed on its copyrights and a contentious "quasi-property" right to facts.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP complaint asserted that AHN reporters had copied facts from AP news reports without permission and without paying a syndication fee.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] After AHN moved to dismiss all but the copyright claims set forth by the AP, a majority of the lawsuit was dismissed.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The case has been dismissed and both parties settled.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] On April 23, 2013, hackers posted a tweet to AP's Twitter account about fictional attacks on the White House, falsely claiming that President Obama had been injured.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The hoax caused a flash crash on the American stock markets, with the Dow Jones Industrial Average briefly falling by 143 points.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] On May 13, 2013, the AP announced that telephone records for 20 of their reporters during a two-month period in 2012 had been subpoenaed by the U.S.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Justice Department and described these acts as a "massive and unprecedented intrusion" into news-gathering operations.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The DOJ did not direct subpoenas to the AP, instead going to their phone providers, including Verizon Wireless.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Attorney General Eric Holder testified under oath in front of the House Judiciary Committee that he recused himself from the leak investigations to avoid any appearance of a conflict of interest.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Holder said his Deputy Attorney General, James M.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Cole, was in charge of the AP investigation and would have ordered the subpoenas.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] On January 10, 2022, AP announced it would start selling non-fungible tokens (NFTs) of their photographs in partnership with a company named Xooa, with the proceeds being used to fund their operations.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] One of the NFTs they promoted on Twitter on 24 February was an aerial shot depicting an overcrowded migrant boat in the Mediterranean Sea by Brazilian photojournalist Felipe Dana.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The sale received negative backlash from users and other journalists, with AP being accused of profiting off of human suffering and the picture choice being "dystopian" and "in extremely poor taste".
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The tweet was subsequently deleted and the NFT, which was to be sold the next day, was pulled from market.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] Global director of media relations Lauren Easton apologized, saying "This was a poor choice of imagery for an NFT.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] It has not and will not be put up for auction ...
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] AP's NFT marketplace is a very early pilot program, and we are immediately reviewing our efforts".
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP has earned 59 Pulitzer Prizes, including 36 for photography, since the award was established in 1917.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] In May 2020, Dar Yasin, Mukhtar Khan, and Channi Anand of the AP were honored with the 2020 Pulitzer Prize for Feature Photography.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The choice caused controversy, because it was taken by some as questioning "India's legitimacy over Kashmir" as it had used the word "independence" in regard to revocation of Article 370.
[src:2024-bolivarian-youth-games/associated-press] The AP won an Oscar in 2024 for the documentary film *20 Days in Mariupol*, a first-person account of the early days of Russia's invasion of Ukraine in 2022.
